<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Canadians Want Curbs on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are growing
suspicious of the Internet and favor government regulation of
cyberspace, according to a poll published today.
</P>
<P>
Canadian women, especially mothers of young children, are
leading the call for Internet control, a year-end Citizen-Global
poll showed.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six Canadians said yes when asked whether they favored
government passing laws to regulate the Internet. Among women in
the 35-54 age group, 80 percent favor regulation.
</P>
<P>
"We have gone beyond the trailblazers, or first wave of users,
who typically would not favor any regulation," said Duncan Mackie,
senior vice-president of POLLARA, the polling firm that conducted
the survey.
</P>
<P>
As the second wave is more likely to consist of families, they
are sensitive to such things as violence and pornography on the
Internet, Mackie said.
</P>
<P>
But David Jones, president of the anti-censorship group
Electronic Frontier Canada, noted that people will change their
minds about regulation the more they use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found that most Canadians don't have access to
the Internet. Sixteen percent have access at work, 13 percent have
access at home and 10 percent have it in both places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
