<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Activists Protest Outside Downing Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Disabled activists threw red
paint today over Downing Street's gate to protest against Prime
Minister Tony Blair's welfare reforms.
</P>
<P>
Around 20 demonstrators spent 90 minutes chained to the gates
of Downing Street, the prime minister's official residence. They
also chanted slogans and held placards against the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The paint was thrown at the gate blocking public access to the
street from Whitehall, a street full of government organizations
and departments.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested around a dozen people, some severely
handicapped, putting them and their wheelchairs to a fleet of
vans.
</P>
<P>
No welfare changes have yet been decided, but the Labor
government's zeal for reform has provoked widespread alarm.
</P>
<P>
Blair has angered disabled groups by refusing to rule out cuts
in some benefits as part of what he sees as a major reform of
Britain's 50-year-old welfare state.
</P>
<P>
A government Green Paper on benefits is due to be published in
later January or early February, a government spokesman said
today. He stressed that Blair was "absolutely determined to drive
it through" despite widespread protest against the reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
