<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Effective Foreign Policy, a Must for Security, Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan Monday underscored the imperatives of an effective
foreign policy which can protect the country's national interests,
security objectives and promote economic development.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address at a seminar on Pakistan's Foreign
Policy for the Next Century, organized by the Institute of
Regional Studies, the foreign minister declared peace and
stability as prerequisites for the development and well-being of
the Pakistani people.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan's geo-strategic situation has to be kept in
mind while developing a security doctrine.
</P>
<P>
The foreign policy has to play a pivotal role in minimizing
external threats and in creating a conducive environment for
economic progress, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan noted that sanctions under the Pressler Amendment
imposed by the United States soon after the withdrawal of the
former Soviet troops from Afghanistan had a major implication for
Pakistan's defense.
</P>
<P>
The enhanced focus by the Clinton administration on South Asia
is encouraging and the two amendments initiated by the
administration are an indication that the United States realizes
that Pakistan has had a raw deal under the discriminatory
non-proliferation laws, he added.
</P>
<P>
For future relations with the United States, Pakistan will have
to enhance economic ties by promoting trade and investments, said
Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
He also said Pakistan's desire for maintaining a strategic
equilibrium in the region and tension-free relations with India
continues to be thwarted by the unresolved Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
On the Afghan issue, the foreign minister said that Pakistan
has no favorites in Afghanistan and is only interested in a
broad-based representative government there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
