<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Urged Not to Make Premature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The co-chairman of the
inter-party dialog, Mainza Chona, today urged opposition leaders
not to make premature public statements which may jeopadize the
arrangements for the meeting to be attended by party presidents
next month to discuss the contentious issues facing the country.
</P>
<P>
Chona, central committee member of the United National
Independence Party (UNIP) led by former president Kenneth Kaunda,
asked all opposition leaders to channel their concerns through
the secretariat set up during the preliminary meeting held early
this month.
</P>
<P>
He said although the first preparatory stage of dialog has
been successfully completed there are more difficult tasks ahead.
</P>
<P>
Chona, who was chosen co-chairman at the preliminary meeting,
said the inter-party dialog secretariat will hold a meeting on
Tuesday to review progress of the dialog process.
</P>
<P>
31 parties attended the preliminary meeting and drew an agenda
for the inter-party dialog.
</P>
<P>
The party presidents will follow the agenda, which includes
most contentious issues like constitution, electoral process and
voters' register and fresh registration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
