<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Agencies Concerned over Cholera Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The international aid
agencies operating in the Somali capital have expressed concern
over the cholera situation in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Committee for the Red Cross
(ICRC), the disease has claimed the lives of 65 people in
Mogadishu and in the neighboring town of Afgoie in a week time.
</P>
<P>
Verena Krebs, ICRC's health delegate in Somalia, said today
hundreds of cholera admissions have been made in an informal
quarantine posts in both towns.
</P>
<P>
Krebs told the journalists here that 313 cholera cases with 40
deaths were reported in the war-ravaged neighborhood of Bermuda,
central Mogadishu. For its insecurity, Bermuda still remains
isolated from the rest of the capital where the aid agencies can
operate.
</P>
<P>
A Mother and Child Health Care unit reports in Mogadishu
indicate that 20 people die of cholera every 72 hours in the
capital alone.
</P>
<P>
According to Krebs, 17 cholera fatalities were reported from
the town of Afgoie, 30 km south of Mogadishu on December 20. She
said both Mogadishu and Afgoie have no single quarantine facility
to cope with the epidemic disease.
</P>
<P>
Somalia is one of eight African countries recently confirmed
by the World Health Organization to be suffering from cholera.
</P>
<P>
"In the other countries, only one percent of the cholera
patients die, while the death rate is 20 percent in Somalia,"said
the ICRC health delegate. The lack of quarantine centers and the
poor sanitation have increased the cases and the easy spread of
the disease, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
