<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor From French Extreme-Right to Re-Arm City Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Jean-Marie Le Chevalier, mayor
of the southern French port city of Toulon who was elected from
the extreme-right National Front (FN), has decided to re-arm 70
city policemen.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made after Interior Minister Jean-Pierre
Chevenement presented a draft law on strictly limiting the
armament of city police forces.
</P>
<P>
The city government of Toulon will arm "as soon as possible"
the police with automatic pistols, which were used by the city
police of Toulon until 1986, the Agence France-Presse quoted city
officials of Toulon as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Three other French cities ruled by FN mayors -- Orange,
Vitrolles and Marignane -- have also expressed strong opposition
to the law on disarming city police.
</P>
<P>
FN leader Jean-Marie Le Pen said in the capital of French
Riviera Nice last Friday that he was "hostile to the disarmament
of city police forces."
</P>
<P>
The disarmament of city police forces has met with strong
opposition from the rightwing PRP government of Nice, a city which
has the largest city police force in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM: All Sides Should Contribute to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today called for efforts by all
parties involved in the Middle East peace process to help push it
forward.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with his Israeli counterpart David Levy here, Qian
said peace is in the best interests of the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
Qian, on the second day of his three-day official visit,
exchanged views with Levy on promoting bilateral relations and
ways to push forward the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Qian told reporters after the talks that China is not playing
the role of a mediator or a coordinator, but it is concerned about
the peace process which has been stalled since last March.
</P>
<P>
He said he is glad to hear from Levy that the Israeli
government is committed to the peace agreements signed with the
Palestinians, and that peace is the only option for Israel.
</P>
<P>
But he urged the Israeli government to give a clear message to
the world that the commitments and agreements are still holding so
that people in this region would feel confident of the peace
process, and the process could move forward.
</P>
<P>
Levy said, "Israel believes that there would be no going-back
in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process. The current government
respects commitments by the former government of Israel in dealing
with the process and will put forward new proposals to push
forward the peace march. Israel hopes to start the final status
talks with the Palestinians for an agreement in order to have a
lasting and overall peace in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
On resuming the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, he said, "it is
misunderstood that Israel wants to resume talks with Syria from
square one, however, there has been no agreement between Israeli
former government and the Syrian side. Nevertheless, Israeli
government is willing to restart the talks with the Syrians on
basis of talks already had and understandings reached."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Chinese delegation quoted Qian as
highlighting during the meeting the importance of the Israeli-Arab
negotiations in the context of the decades of conflicts in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we believe the principle of 'land for peace' should
be adhered to and all sides should adopt a more flexible,
realistic and positive approach to make the peace process moving."
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China understands Israel's security needs and
opposes any violent actions from any sides, but peace and
security can not be separated from one another. The current
impasse of peace process is detrimental to both Israelis and
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, both sides expressed satisfaction,
saying that they should exchange more visits to further promote
the existing friendly ties and expand cooperation in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister arrived here Sunday night from
Syrian capital Damascus, the second leg of his current Middle East
tour which has also taken him to Lebanon. He is scheduled to meet
Israeli President Ezer Weizman and Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu later today.
</P>
<P>
He is also going to visit the Palestinian self-rule area and
Egypt after concluding his visit here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
