<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unrest Surges in Kenya as Poll Day Approaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Commission (EC)
of Kenya today called on all political leaders to make efforts to
curb the surging election-related violence as the campaign for
the presidency is running to the top gear.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said two more people were killed in the
country's third-largest city of Kisumu over weekend following
clashes between supporters of the National Development Party
(NDP) and youths allegedly backing the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU).
</P>
<P>
Thus it has brought the toll of those dead since November 15
to about 10 with more than 80 injured and dozens arrested across
the country. The poll was scheduled for next Monday.
</P>
<P>
EC Chairman Samuel Kivuitu told a press conference today that
he has asked political party leaders to attend a meeting on
Wednesday to discuss how to avoid and stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
"I have invited the main political leaders to press on the
issue of violence. It is essential that we meet them since the
remaining days are of the greatest significance to the
sovereignty of Kenya," said Kivuitu.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that his commission received complaints on
violence from the NDP and the Social Democratic Party (SDP),
another main opposition party over the weekends and "now consider
what action it will take".
</P>
<P>
There were also conflicting reports about turmoil involving
the opposition Safina party and KANU in Garissa, Northeastern
Province on Sunday, leaving 10 people injured.
</P>
<P>
However, the police reportedly claimed there was no violence,
only "angry words" between Safina and KANU supporters.
</P>
<P>
Later today, KANU spokesman Fallana Ogw strongly condemned the
recent violence behind which he said there is no KANU's hand.
</P>
<P>
The KANU always pursues peace, love and unity among Kenyan
people who should be ensured "the opportunity for free and fair
poll", he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Nine of the total 15 presidential candidates had requested and
been given round-the-clock security. Those who have not applied
include aspirants from FORD-People, Kenya, UPPK, FORD-Asili and
Umma.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Kenyan President and KANU Chairman Daniel arap Moi,
73 and in power for 19 years, is widely expected to win his last
campaign with five-year more tenure largely due to the division
of the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
