<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Christmas Cost in Britain Goes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain's retailers are pinning
hopes of a recovery in December sales on the last several days
before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Trading in the high street was slower than expected last week
and many stores and shops have already begun discounting in an
attempt to woo shoppers.
</P>
<P>
The bill for the average family's Christmas is 209.50 pounds
(335.2 US dollars), down nine pounds (14.4 US dollars) from last
year's total and the first fall in at least four years, according
to the Christmas price index.
</P>
<P>
However, another report published today forecasts spending in
the January sales on non-food products to be as high as 6.7
billion pounds (10.72 billion US dollars), equivalent to 9 percent
more than January 1997.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that much of the 20 billion pound (32 billion US
dollar) windfall money from building society conversions has
already been spent on large electrical goods and holidays rather
than Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Economics and Business Research (CEBR) forecast
up to 3 billion pounds (4.8 billion US dollars) of stock in the
non-food sector would be carried over into the January sales.
</P>
<P>
Douglas McWilliams of the CEBR said that five interest rate
rises since May, tax increases and uncertainty on the stock market
since the autumn had damped down trading activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
