<HEADLINE> Heavy Traffic Expected on Major Roads in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The South African
traffic authorities today warned motorists nationwide of
increased traffic volumes expected on all major routes from
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Arrive Alive National Traffic Information Center (NTIC)
urged motorists to drive slower as rain and storms were forecast.
</P>
<P>
The center said the peak was expected to begin on Tuesday at
midday and would reach the highest numbers between 7:00 PM and
8:00 PM.
</P>
<P>
Traffic on Tuesday was expected to comprise travellers going
away or visiting family for the Christmas weekend.
</P>
<P>
"They will not be travelling very far and accidents will occur
over short distances and in municipal areas," the center said.
</P>
<P>
The Weather Bureau predicted rain across the country on
Tuesday, with torrential downpours expected in Gauteng Province
and the Free State, and mist on the escarpment of Kwazulu Natal
Province, Mpumalanga Province and the Northern Province.
</P>
<P>
In its latest fatality report, the NTIC said high speed and
pedestrian jay-walking were the highest contributory factors to
the increasing fatality rate, currently standing at 427.
</P>
<P>
The NTIC urged drivers to rest before embarking on a long
journey and take sufficient stops along the way to stretch the
limbs and relax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
