<HEADLINE> De Beers to Operate Independently </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
well-known mining company Anglo American and Diamond Giant De
Beers announced today they had agreed to restructure their
business links to allow the latter to operate as a separate,
independently-managed company.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the two groups said that the move would
help De Beers meet future challenges and opportunities of the
diamond industry with a fully independent and dedicated
management team.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, De Beers would become a self-administered
and free standing international organization with its own staff.
</P>
<P>
All employees in the diamond services division of Anglo
American would be offered employment with De Beers with effect
from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
De Beers would cancel its existing service agreements with
Anglo American against payment of a negotiated amount, and
establish its own service departments to replace the services
currently drawn from Anglo American.
</P>
<P>
After its independence, De Beers would remain the largest
shareholder in Anglo American. Its registered head office would
continue to be in Kimberley, Northern Cape Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
