<HEADLINE> Greece, Iran, Armenia Sign Memorandum of Understanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Greece, Iran and Armenia today
signed a memorandum of understanding to further strengthen their
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, which was inked after a tripartite
meeting of their foreign ministers here, the three countries will
cooperate in the sectors of transport, postal services,
telecommunications, tourism, industry, technology and energy.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos and his Iranian and
Armenian counterparts, Kamal Kharrazi and Alexander Arzoumanian,
also decided to arrange meetings of experts in these sectors early
next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after their talks, Pangalos said
that the three countries also wanted to further their cooperation
in other sectors, and the foreign ministers would meet for this
purpose again next year.
</P>
<P>
Arzoumanian hailed the bilateral relations between the three
countries as "excellent." He added that the memorandum would help
expand their economic cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers of Iran and Armenia also met with
Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos, Prime Minister Costas
Simitis and Parliament President Apostolos Kaklamanis.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite cooperation began in 1995 and the last meeting
at ministerial level took place in Tehran in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
