<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industries Minister Complains of Bureaucracy in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Industries Minister
Gholamreza Shafei has complained of excessive bureaucracy in the
country, saying that it hinders the expansion of the country's
non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
The government would not be able to achieve the 1.9 billion
U.S. dollar goal of non-oil industrial exports for the current
Iranian fiscal year starting on March 21 due to excessive
bureaucracy, Shafei was quoted by Iranian official IRNA news
agency as saying today.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate bureaucracy in the country. However,
foreign businessmen have complained of the complicated procedures
at the country's customs and ministries, and the banks.
</P>
<P>
They said that one must go to various state institutions to get
permissions and confirmations and the issue would be more serious
if one tries to import goods for Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran started a strict control on financial and monetary
affairs and obliged Iranian merchants to do their business
through the country's banking system after the country faced a
problem of repayment to foreign debts following the sharp fall of
oil prices in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Shafei expressed the hope that the country's
development would be accelerated with the expansion of industrial
sectors, saying that some 9,500 industrial units have obtained
licenses and started operations during the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
At present 8,000 new industrial units are under construction,
he added, stressing that more efforts should be made to
improve the situation and to define priorities for industrial
sector such as electronics, car manufacturing, chemicals and
textile production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
