<HEADLINE> Probe Into Foiled Coup Underway in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military said here
today that investigation into Sunday's coup plot involving the
country's second person Lt. Gen. Oladipo Diya is underway.
</P>
<P>
A press release signed by the military spokesman Col. Godwin
Ugbo, said the coup attempt "to violently overthrow the present
administration" took place in early hours on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ddiya and 11 others, including one civilian, are the
"principal actors" and have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
"Further investigation has commenced," it said, adding that
the government would "strongly resist any attempt to undermine
the security and integrity of the nation and thereby derail the
on-going transition to a democratically elected government".
</P>
<P>
"With the just concluded elections to state houses of
assembly, the federal military government reassures that the
transition to a civil rule is very much on course and will be
pursued to a logical conclusion", it said.
</P>
<P>
The press release also gave a list of the "principal actors",
on top of which is Diya, chief of general staff and vice-chairman
of the ruling Provisional Ruling Council.
</P>
<P>
Diya, 53, reportedly escaped from a bomb blast last on
December 13 at the presidential wing of the international airport
of Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The other coup plotters include former minister of works and
housing Major-general Abul-Karim Adisa and former minister of
communications Major-general Tajudeen Olanrewaju, both of whom
were sacked in the cabinet reshuffle last month.
</P>
<P>
Among those arrested are also four colonels, one Lt.-colonel
and three majors, who are either close to Diya or the other two
major-generals.
</P>
<P>
The only civilian, identified as Professor Feimi Odekunle, is
the political adviser to Diya.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's announcement of the botched plot brought to two the
number of known attempts to unseat the administration of General
Sani Abacha who came into power on November 17, 1993.
</P>
<P>
The first took place in March 1995, involving former head of
state General Olusegun Obasanjo, the retired general now kept in
jail, and his deputy late Major-general Musa Shehu Yar'adua, who
died serving a 25-year imprisonment a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Since the independence in 1960, Nigeria has witnessed five
successful coups and three aborted ones.
</P>
<P>
It seems that Sunday's foiled coup has not made great fuss in
Nigeria so far and the situation in the country is calm up to
now.
</P>
<P>
Although official announcement of the cause of the coup
attempt is yet to come, observers here said it might have
connections with last month's reshuffle of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In the 33-member reconstituted cabinet Abacha swore in last
Thursday, less than half of the former ministers are reappointed.
</P>
<P>
Another focus of attention goes to the fact that most of the
coup plotters belong to the tribe of Yeruba in the east, while
the power of the country is generally held by men from the Hausa
tribe in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
