<HEADLINE> 20 People Die on S. African Roads Every Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- About 20 people were
killed every day on South African roads since the beginning of
the month, the National Traffic Information Center said today.
</P>
<P>
The death toll nationwide has climbed to 427 as for today,
according to the center.
</P>
<P>
The figure is much lower compared with the same period last
year. A total of 1,242 people lost their lives from December 3,
1996 to January 12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Most accidents were caused by speeding, traffic officials
said. Of about 770,000 fines issued for traffic offenses since
October when a nationwide "Arrive Alive" road safety campaign
began, some 481,000, or more than 60 percent, were for speeding.
</P>
<P>
The country sees most traffic accidents during the Christmas
and New Year season when more people drive long ways to their
holiday destinations.
</P>
<P>
Traffic volumes on major national routes are expected to
increase significantly. The N3 route from Johannesburg to Durban
and N1 to Cape Town are considered to be very dangerous during
this period.
</P>
<P>
Four people were killed and several others were injured on
Sunday night when two minibuses in which they were travelling in
collided near Vereeniging, some 60 kilometers south of
Johannesburg, while road accidents in the Pretoria area claimed
five lives at the weekend, South African Press Association
reported today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
