<HEADLINE> Cyprus Favours Improved Greco-Turkish Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus favors all efforts
aimed at improving Greco-Turkish relations as well as Turkey's
European prospects, a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Manolis Christofides
said that Greco-Turkish friendship would imply a solution to the
Cyprus problem in the framework of U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Christofides noted that the Cypriot government supports
Turkey's aspirations for getting a European Union membership,
pointing out, however, that Ankara should respect the
preconditions set by the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's European prospect will also depend on the progress
achieved in the Cyprus problem, and on abandoning its policy of
trying to obstruct Cyprus' accession to the EU," the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent meeting in Washington between
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz, Christofides expressed satisfaction because the Cyprus
problem was among the issues discussed.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the U.S. has repeatedly stated that the
Cyprus problem ranks high in its list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
"A solution to the Cyprus problem would serve vital American
interests in the area," Christofides added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the prospects for a Cyprus settlement in the
coming year, Christofides said that many foreign officials have
described 1998 as "the year for Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"If all interested parties show good will, the Cyprus problem
will not take long to be solved," he remarked.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
