<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is to encourage
private entrepreneurs to open new businesses to attract more
laborers, Radio Uganda reported today.
</P>
<P>
At the closing ceremony of the second three-week business
skills development course, Richard Kaijuka, the minister for
planning and economic development, disclosed that the government
is working out a scheme for commercial banks to financially
assist entrepreneurs to open new business ventures to attract
more labourers.
</P>
<P>
The minister reaffirmed the government policy to pull-out from
business, and asked the businessmen to avoid the dependency on
the government. The government is encouraging businessmen to
generate their incomes, Kaijuka said.
</P>
<P>
Chuama, the deputy of the resident representative of United
Nation Development Program in Uganda, appealed to Ugandans to
concentrate their efforts on eradication of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Henry Kanyika, the chairman for Uganda Manufacture Association
(UMA), said on the occasion that UMA will work with government
and development partners in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
The three-week course was funded by UNDP and organized by UMA.
</P>
