<HEADLINE> Junta Dismisses Kabbah's Trip to S. Leone as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the military
junta in Sierra Leone today dismissed as a "cosmetic venture"
what he called the "flying visit of deposed president Tejan
Kabbah to Sierra Leone for the first time since he was overthrown
in May.
</P>
<P>
"He needn't have come sneaking into the country in which he is
a citizen and sought the help of Nigerian troops for this," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the (military) government has "always said
that Kabbah is free to return so that he, Sankon (the rebel
leader now detained in Nigeria) and Major Koroma can sit down and
work out a comprehensive plan for sustainable peace in Sierra
Leone."
</P>
<P>
Kabbah, accompanied by a number of his ministers in exile in
neighboring Guinea including vice president Joe Demby and deputy
defense minister Hinga Norman who heads the Kamajors, addressed
Nigerian troops in ECOMOG at their base at the Lungi
International Airport, 10 miles across the Sierra Leone estuary
but did not visit the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Journalists from the mainland were prevented by Nigerian
securities from attending the ceremony and their dugout canoes
were intercepted by ECOMOG gunboats and ordered to turn away.
</P>
<P>
According to local residents at Lungi, Kabbah looked slightly
nervous as he spoke, thanking the Nigerian soldiers for "giving
adequate security" to the people in the area.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah said his visit "is the beginning of regular
consultation with the people of Sierra Leone as he would be
coming from time to time for the people to know that he as their
leader has not forsaken them," one eye witness said.
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared to wait until April 22, 1998 because I have
already given my word to the international community and the
ECOWAS leaders as well," Kabbah said.
</P>
<P>
According to one local chief, "Kabbah's visit came as a great
surprise as we have been expecting him since mid November when
the visit was called off without explanation."
</P>
<P>
Another resident said the visit "has pushed back speculations
about an ECOMOG attack on Freetown over the Christmas period."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
