<HEADLINE> US Insurance Industry Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Property and casualty
insurers in the United States fared well in 1997 while a moderate
growth of the industry is forecast for 1998, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Earned premiums of property and casualty insurance are expected
to reach 272 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, compared to 263.4
billion dollars in 1996, according to the Insurance Information
Institute (III), an industry group.
</P>
<P>
Investment income of the industry is expected to amount to 41.5
billion dollars against 38 billion dollars in 1996, while capital
gains could go up to 9.9 billion dollars from 9.2 billion, the III
said.
</P>
<P>
The industry paid 3.5 billion dollars for catastrophe losses
compared to 7.4 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Analysts see "serious threats" to the industry in the long-term
and depression of rates because of continuing competition. They
expect premiums to grow modestly but capital gains and investment
income to fall next year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. insurance industry employs about 2.2 million people at
a payroll of 83 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
