<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Summit Ends with Major Decisions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The three-day summit of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states ended here today with a
number of important decisions aimed at strengthening regional
security, stability and internal cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
In their final communique issued at the end of the summit, the
six Gulf leaders from Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain and Oman expressed satisfaction with the
steps taken in all areas related to internal cooperation and
relations with regional countries during the summit.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, the leaders approved recommendations by
defense ministers on linking the GCC states' radar and
communications network, early warning system and military
training as part of security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The leaders "expressed satisfaction with the steps taken in
all areas of military cooperation" as described in the final
communique.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, projects of a proposed optic fibers cable
and the "Cooperation Security Belt" which links radar and air
warning networks of the GCC armies will be enacted within
two years. They are expected to pave the way for creating
a joint operation room able to deal with threats to any
member state.
</P>
<P>
On relations with Iran, the final communique expressed hope for
establishing good relations with Iran based on mutual respect and
the principle of non-interference in internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The GCC leaders said in the communique that the coming era will
witness positive and concrete trust-building steps to establish
relations which guarantee security and stability in the region in
view of the positive statements by Iranian officials to start a
new era of relations with the GCC.
</P>
<P>
But the GCC leaders also reiterated their full support for the
UAE sovereignty over the islands of Greater and Lesser Tunbs and
Abu Musa now occupied by Iran.
</P>
<P>
The leaders urged Iraq to "fulfill all U.N. Security Council
resolutions without selection," especially those calling for the
elimination of its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
They said that Iraqi compliance with U.N. resolutions would
help end the U.N. sanctions "to ease the suffering of the Iraqi
people, a matter that draws the sympathy of the GCC countries."
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, the leaders condemned
Israeli hard-line policy, categorically rejected the Israeli
government's actions and demand a full compliance with the
signed accords with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
They expressed support for the legitimate right of the
Palestinian people, including the right to establish an
independent state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The GCC leaders called on Israel to resume peace talks with
Syria and Lebanon from where they were suspended and called for
"an immediate and unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
On the economic cooperation front, the leaders gave the
go-ahead to start the implementation of a project to link
the power grid of the six member countries into an integrated
network. The first phase which is expected to cost 2.2
billion U.S. dollars will complete in two years.
</P>
<P>
To enhance the banking cooperation, the leaders agreed to
allow Gulf banks to open branches in the six member countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also agreed to set up a Consultative Council,
approved environment protection systems and ratified a unified
civil code and a penal code as well as a number of other decisions
to push forward the internal cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Observers here hold that the results and achievements of
the summit, whether the positive attitude toward improving
ties with Iran and a more reconciliatory stand to Iraq, or
the decisions in the fields of military and economic
cooperation, will for sure push the GCC countries into a
new and more forward-looking era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Uzbekistan Reach Six Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Uzbekistan signed
six major documents in Tashkent, Uzbekistan, today, the first day
of the visit of Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported from Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
Two of the signed documents are intergovernmental agreements on
encouraging and mutual protection of investments and on science
and technology cooperation in the peaceful use of nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
The other agreements were reached on bilateral cooperation and
mutual assistance in counteracting illegal financial operations
and financial operations linked with the legalization of
illegally-earned funds (money laundry).
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a protocol on the results of the
session of the intergovernmental commission for economic
cooperation between Uzbekistan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Abdumannon Makhmudov, deputy head of the Uzbekistan Cabinet of
Ministers' department for coordinating foreign economic activity,
said that the documents will undoubtedly promote the development
of bilateral cooperation and consolidate the legal basis for
boosting mutually beneficial relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin arrived in Tashkent today for a two-day working
visit. The leaders of the two countries are due to examine a wide
range of questions relating to the development of trade, economic,
military and technical cooperation, and interaction in the customs
sphere. 
</P>
