<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Companies Hasty for Cable TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Several of the largest cable
television companies in the U.S. announced plans last week to buy
15 million digital set-top boxes from Nextlevel Systems Inc., a
move that could sharply accelerate the use of new digital services
by TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between the potential buyers and seller will
indicate a far larger television business, the New York Times
reported today. The computer industry wants to provide the
processors and operating systems for all these new digital boxes,
and the cable industry appears to be a receptive customer.
</P>
<P>
Some experts agreed that "the world of the future is the world
of the network PC."
</P>
<P>
Although final technical specifications have not yet been
issued, the digital TV set-top devices will actually be powerful
computers. Unlike the conventional analog boxes in use today,
these new devices will be able to process high-speed digital
signals moving to and from the home.
</P>
<P>
They will enable cable companies to expand the number of
channels they offer. And they will also make possible new
generations of television-based interactive services, including
high-speed Internet access with E-mail, on-demand pay-per-view
videos, push-button electronic commerce, advertising that can be
aimed to specific homes, interactive games and eventually
high-definition video, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the speed of the deployment of these boxes
depends in large part on the cable companies' ability to upgrade
their existing analog systems. That can be a slow and expensive
process. To raise money to pay for new cable and optical fiber
networks and millions of the expensive new boxes, the companies
are actively looking for big investors.
</P>
<P>
The Microsoft Corporation, the nation's software giant, spend 1
billion U.S. dollars separately to buy WebTV and part of Comcast
to promote its cable TV system.
</P>
<P>
Nextlevel says it plans to sell the next-generation boxes for
about 300 U.S. dollars each, meaning the deal announced last week
could be worth as much as 4.5 billion U.S. dollars to the company
over the next three years. Tele-Communications, the largest
customer, agreed to buy 10 million of the boxes.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that dozens of companies also joined the
competition for setting the standard for new digital services.
They include IBM, Sun Microsystems, Scientific Atlanta, Toshiba,
Cisco Systems, and Lucent Technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
