<HEADLINE> Egyptian Statement on Somali Talks Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The National Salvation
Council (NSC) of Somalia today strongly condemned a statement by
the Egyptian Foreign Ministry spokesperson regarding the Somali
reconciliation talks in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Two NSC co-chairmen General Aden Abdullahi Nur and Col.
Abdullahi Yusuf Ahmed dismissed it as irresponsible and
misleading to the international community.
</P>
<P>
A press release jointly signed by the two co- chairmen and
issued here today said, "it was irresponsible on the part of
Egypt to claim that a historic agreement had been reached at
Somali Cairo talks while the whole world knew that two
co-chairmen of the NSC left Cairo after an impasse on key issues
and lack of consensus even within NSC itself."
</P>
<P>
It added, "moreover, the Egyptian statement ignores the wishes
and participation of the people in the north of Somalia, thus
discrediting once again the impartial mediation by that
government among Somali political factions."
</P>
<P>
The press release pointed out that "the Egyptian government
has hijacked the Somali reconciliation process and as a result
has created more divisions within Somali factions, thus seriously
damaging the efforts and gains of seven years of reconciliation
among Somali faction leaders."
</P>
<P>
The NSC co-chairmen noted "the government of Egypt is biased
as it is not sincere in resolving the Somali crisis."
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier announcement here by the NSC
spokesman, Somali factions meeting in Cairo failed to reach
agreement on a number of key issues, including the venue of the
national reconciliation conference, the fair representation of
clans in the conference and the withdrawal of Hussein Aideed's
militia from certain occupied districts of Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
