<HEADLINE> S. African Teachers' Employment to Depend on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of teachers
employed by a province would in future depend on provincial
budgets and no longer on fixed teacher to pupil ratios, the South
African Department of Education said today.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, the number of teachers employed by a province has
been determined by the National Edcuation Department.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Sibusiso Bengu said in Pretoria that the
new move was in line with the government's decision to terminate
its existing right-sizing process with effect from January 1 next
year.
</P>
<P>
In terms of this process, which came into effect last year,
the department hoped to achieve teacher to pupil ratios of 1:35
for high schools and 1:40 for primary schools by 2000.
</P>
<P>
It aimed to do this by redeploying teachers at schools with an
abundance of educators to less fortunate schools, a process
already underway.
</P>
<P>
The changes themselves did not threaten the employment of a
single teacher. "The measures only provide a framework," Bengu
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
