<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Sales of new apartment in Israel fell by 8 percent
in the private sector in the third quarter this year compared to
the same period last year, the Jerusalem Post daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics, a total
of 3,790 new apartments were sold in the 24 largest cities in the
third quarter of 1997, while 4,110 were sold in the same period of
1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli national carrier El Al and Air France were
negotiating an agreement for flights between Tel Aviv and Paris,
the latest issue of Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an El Al spokesman as saying that the
agreement would mean alternating flights by the two companies,
which would carry passengers interchangeably.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Nigeria are Africa's top investment
attractors, local newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released by the United Nations Economic
Commission on Africa, 50 percent of the total foreign direct
investments in Africa from 1981 to 1996 had gone to Egypt and
Nigeria, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's People's Assembly had passed a law to reduce
the income tax ceiling to 40 percent from 48 percent, the Egyptian
Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The law also increased tax-free income allowances to a maximum
of 3,000 Egyptian pounds (884 U.S. dollars) from 1,680 pounds (495
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Finance Minister Hohieddin Abu Bakr Al-Gharib had said
the cuts would cost the treasury about 245 million pounds (72
million dollars) a year, but were in line with "government policy
to ease burdens on citizens, particularly low-income people and
encourage investment."
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- More than 150 Egyptian public companies of iron and
steel, minerals, spinning and weaving, transport and
telecommunications would be privatized by the end of next year,
the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Advisor of the Ministry of Public Business Sector Sabri Aglan
said Sunday a new company would be set up soon for restructuring
120 stumbling public companies.
</P>
<P>
He added the Arab-Egyptian Investment Fund formed Saturday with
a capital of 1 billion pounds (294 million dollars) would be a
buffer zone to investors against any economic shocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
