<HEADLINE> Floods Halting Tanzanian Railway Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian Railways
Corporation (TRC) will not risk resuming passenger train services
on the lines of Tabora-Mwanza and Tabora-Kigoma due to the floods
which have swept most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The TRC Director General, Linford Mbomba made the remarks here
today that the services have been halted by floods and will not
resume until the situation improves.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot take the risk of operating passenger trains on the
two lines as requested by the Tabora Regional Commissioner,
Stephen Mashishanga," he maintained.
</P>
<P>
Mboma said the TRC authorities are afraid of causing problems
and incoveniences to passengers in case of any accidents.
Normally when an accident happens, the corporation will have to
compensate the passengers, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to run into trouble," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Tabora Regional Commissioner last Sunday appealed to the
TRC authorities to resume passenger services on the two lines,
saying that most of the roads in the region are not passable and
thus making movement of both people and goods difficult.
</P>
<P>
Following the suspension of train services along the Central
railway line, thousands of passengers are being stranded.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Dodoma Regional Commissioner, Isidore Shirima
said 150 tons of relief food destined for Kondoa district are
stranded in Dodoma after a road section was destroyed by the
lasting rains.
</P>
<P>
TRC suspended train services along the Central railway line
mid-December after floods washed away several sections. After
repairs, it went into operation. But merciless floods damaged
more sections, forcing it to suspend services again.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the Kakindo Village in the northwest region of
Kagera, 789 families have been rendered homeless after heavy
floods swept away their houses, reports reaching here said.
</P>
</TEXT>
