<HEADLINE> Security Council Again Urges Iraq to Cooperate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today issued a presidential statement, once
again calling on the Iraqi government to cooperate fully with the
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
The move came after Richard Butler, executive chairman of the
UNSCOM in charge of dismantling Iraqi weapons of mass destruction,
briefed the council on his four-day visit to Iraq last week.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Butler said his talks
with Iraqi officials on dismantling Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction had yield little progress.
</P>
<P>
In the presidential statement, the council reiterated its
demand that the government of Iraq cooperate fully with the UNSCOM
in accordance with all relevant resolutions and the government of
Iraq allow UN weapons inspection teams immediate, unconditional
access to any and all areas, facilities, equipment, records and
means of transportation which they wish to inspect in accordance
with the mandate of the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed that the failure by the government of Iraq
to provide the UNSCOM with immediate and unconditional access to
any site and category of sites was unacceptable and a clear
violation of te relevant resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated that the effectiveness and speed with
which the UNSCOM may accomplish its responsibilities was, above
all, determined by the degree to which the government of Iraq
cooperates in disclosing the full extent and disposition of its
proscribed programs and in granting the UNSCOM unimpeded access to
all sites, documents, records, and individuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
