<HEADLINE> Israeli President Meets Chinese Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During their meeting in the Presidential residence, Weizman
first welcomed Qian's visit to Israel. He highly praised the
fast development of Sino-Israeli relations in various areas.
</P>
<P>
Qian relayed greetings from Chinese President Jiang Zemin to
Weizman, and he invited the president to visit China at a
convenient time. Weizman, who was scheduled to visit China at
the year end, has postponed his visit, citing domestic reasons.
</P>
<P>
Qian introduced to Weizman the current state of China's
economic and political development and their prospects. He pointed
out that it would take painstaking efforts for China to become
a developed country in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The minister refuted the claim that China will pose threats
to the world stability once it becomes developed. He noted
that only when China stays underdeveloped and poor will it
threaten the world stability, otherwise it will only contribute
to the world peace.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed satisfaction with the current state of
bilateral relationship, hoping they would be further developed.
</P>
<P>
Weizman explained Israeli positions on the Middle East peace
process, saying that he was still optimistic about the prospects
for the peace in the region despite the current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Expressing the belief that the 21st century should become a
peaceful century free of wars and conflicts, Qian stressed the
importance of achieving stability and peace in the Middle East,
which he said will help contribute to the world stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that in order to realize peace, stability and
development in the region, the parties concerned in the peace
process should make quick progress through conducting serious
negotiations with flexibility and on the basis of the United
Nations resolutions and the principle of land-for-peace.
</P>
