<HEADLINE> Draft Protocol on Gulf Marine Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The eight Gulf littoral states
concluded here today a draft protocol on the control of marine
trans-boundary movements of endangered species and other wastes,
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The draft was formulated at the fourth meeting of the
legal and technical experts of the Kuwait-based Regional
Organization for Protection of Marine Environment (ROPME),
sponsored by Iranian Organization for Environment Protection
(IOEP).
</P>
<P>
The IRNA did not specify the details about the draft protocol,
only saying that the protocol will take effect after the final
approval of the ROPME member states and the Kuwaiti government
serves as the trustee for the document.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Vice President and head of the IOEP Masoumeh
Ebtekar expressed her confidence that through cooperation and
coordination of the member states, the provision for security
and protection of the marine environment would be substantiated.
</P>
<P>
She said that the major marine pollution results from oil
and endangered species and other wastes, from shipping accidents
and emergencies in the sea and the land-based pollution
sources.
</P>
<P>
Ebtekar voiced Iran's readiness to develop long-term
cooperation with the regional organization in putting the
protocol into practice and to hold further scientific and
technical meetings for implementing the protocol.
</P>
<P>
The ROPME groups Bahrain, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
