<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Calls for Realistic Attitudes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today called for Israelis and
Palestinians to take realistic and positive attitudes towards
pushing forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a meeting with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu here which covered the Middle East peace
process and the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the whole peace process would only advance on
the basis of abiding by the relevant U.N. resolutions and sticking
to the principle of land-for-peace.
</P>
<P>
He told Netanyahu that there will be no security at all if
peace is not realized. He expressed the belief that countries in
the region including Israel will enjoy real peace only after the
region achieves a comprehensive, just and lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China hopes the Middle East peace process will be
resumed on all tracks at an earlier date.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Netanyahu explained Israeli positions on the
peace process, expressing his willingness to make peace with all
his country's neighbors under the condition that its security is
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Both sides expressed satisfaction with the smooth development
of bilateral relations since the two countries established
diplomatic ties in 1992. Netanyahu said a solid basis has been
laid for the future development of such ties, especially in the
agricultural field.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the increase in high-level contacts
and exchange of visits show that considerable achievements have
been gained in mutual cooperations in the spheres of politics,
economy, culture and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Qian said Beijing welcomes Israeli entrepreneures, businessmen
and Jews around the world to invest or do business in China.
</P>
<P>
Qian conveyed greetings from Chinese Premier Li Peng to
Netanyahu, and invited Netanyahu to visit China.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, who arrived here Sunday from visits to
Lebanon and Syria, briefed Netanyahu on his meetings with Lebanese
and Syrian leaders.
</P>
<P>
