<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Urged for Cooperation for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides today called on Turkish Cypriots to
cooperate in efforts to reach a settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman issued the call while commenting on an article
entitled "Abandoned by the World" written by Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash, which was published recently on the Turkish
Cypriot press.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said that if Denktash feels abandoned, "he has
his policy to blame and the crimes Turkey has committed
against Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Turkish Cypriots have their place in the
Republic of Cyprus, stressing that "if we cooperate we can
gradually establish the federal, bizonal, bicommunal Republic of
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Christofides also pointed out that both Denktash and Turkish
officials recently stepped up efforts to achieve recognition of
the secessionist entity unilaterally declared in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the international community does not and will
not recognize the Turkish Cypriot regime set up in the occupied
north.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third of the
island following a short-lived pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was only recognized
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also dismissed Denktash's claims that the
European Union (EU) decision, taken in Luxembourg earlier this
month, to start accession talks with Cyprus in spring 1998 is
like "offering Greek Cypriots union (with Greece) on a silver
platter."
</P>
<P>
"The Luxembourg decision offers Greek and Turkish Cypriot
youth the chance to become Europeans," Christofides said, adding
that "we should take advantage of this opportunity."
</P>
<P>
Both Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot community object to the
EU's decision to start accession talks with the Cypriot
government, insisting that Cyprus can join the EU only after a
political settlement on the island. 
</P>
