<HEADLINE> Ghanaians Reported Facing Acute Fuel Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaians, who are to suffer a
nationwide electricity rationing beginning next year, have come
to blows over the diminishing fuel supply.
</P>
<P>
Short supply of petrol in the capital Accra since the weekend
has led to thefts and injuries in fighting for fuel, a report
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
As long queues formed on Sunday at the few filling stations
with fuel stocks, tempers flared and scuffles broke out,
prompting one dealer to call the police.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a filling station manager as saying that his
stock of 13,500 liters of petrol sold out in three hours.
</P>
<P>
Taxi drivers have increased their prices as signs reading "no
fuel here" appear at filling stations across the capital.
</P>
<P>
Many tourists hoping to travel to various destinations in
Ghana have been stranded in Accra.
</P>
<P>
The report said, Chief Executive of the Tema Oil Refinery,
William Parker, has come under fire for not taking appropriate
steps after a foreign fuel supplier failed to make promised
deliveries in November.
</P>
<P>
According to the government's electricity rationing plan
announced last Friday, non-essential industries and private
electricity consumers across the country will suffer a 12-hour
power cut three times a week beginning January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
But hospitals and other essential consumers will not be
affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
