<HEADLINE> Gulf Leaders Call for International Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) leaders today condemned all aspects of terrorism and
violence and called for international efforts to fight against
them.
</P>
<P>
In the final communique issued at the end of a three-day annual
summit here, the leaders expressed regret over the fact that "some
states are giving refuge to certain terrorist elements under the
pretext of human right protection."
</P>
<P>
They called for the "differentiation between human rights and
the acts committed by these elements against states and human
alike."
</P>
<P>
Without naming the states that are hiding terrorists, the
leaders appealed to them to act against the use of their lands and
laws by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
They also called for the adoption of an international treaty to
fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1981, the GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar,
Bahrain, Oman and the United Arab Emirates in an economic and
political alliance.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the GCC leaders rejected and denounced
"European Parliament and other international organizations and
agencies' interference in the judicial system of GCC states."
</P>
<P>
They considered the move as "unacceptable interference in GCC
internal affairs which could encourage crime and terrorist acts
and accordingly affect security and stability."
</P>
<P>
On November 23, the GCC interior ministers rejected the
European Union allegations of "human rights violations in
Bahrain," where the authorities were able to contain a series of
subversive acts since the start of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
