<HEADLINE> New York City Sees Growing Traffic Congestion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Booming tourism and strong
economy have added more traffic jams to the New York City,
especially its commercial heart of Manhattan area.
</P>
<P>
Total traffic from neighboring New Jersey State rose 5 percent
from 1996 to a record number of 85.2 million vehicle crossings
this year, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from Manhatan's 16,464 parking meters also saw a record
surge of 18.8 percent to 22.39 million U.S. dollars in 1997, plus
a revenue growth of 16 percent to 6.5 million dollars in the
city's public parking lots, not taking into account private
parking income.
</P>
<P>
The "too many cars for too few streets" scene has caused the
traffic congestion a worsening problem. Statistics show that
midtown city streets have seen an unprecedented slow traffic
averaging 6.2 miles an hour this year.
</P>
<P>
Traffic violations have soared with 20,437 summons issued and
755 cars towed since Thanksgiving this year.
</P>
<P>
To improve the situation, city transportation authorities have
made a number of proposals, such as engaging more use of railroads
and subways.
</P>
<P>
A new subway fare system was introduced early this month to
attract more public transport commuters and reduce the car traffic
volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
