<HEADLINE> Iran to Buy 100 Locomotives from France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran today signed an agreement
worth 200 million U.S. dollars to buy 100 locomotives from France,
the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here by managing director of Iran's
state railway company Rahman Dadman, managing director of the
Iranian Vagonsazi Pars company as supplier, and an executive of
Alstom company of France as manufacturer side of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Alstom will initially supply 20
locomotives to Iran's state railway company and another five
assembled by Iran's Wagonsazi Pars company.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 75 units are to be assembled by Wagonsazi Pars
company after transfer of technology from the French manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
Alstom has undertaken to supply those locomotives in less than
five years, and the first 20 to be delivered to Iran in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
Managing director of the Iran's state railway company Dadman
said that the railway had also entered into separate
agreements with two Iranian manufacturers for transfer of
locomotive manufacturing technology and motor traction. 
</P>
