Yilmaz said today that the United States sees Turkey as an
important strategic partner, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz made the remark upon his arrival at the Ankara
Airport following his official visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. clearly expressed that it regards Turkey as a
strategic partner and is aware of Turkey's importance in the
region," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
As a result of this approach, the U.S. administration is
willing to cooperate with Turkey in the fields of politics,
economy, trade as well as defense, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister said that the two countries will
also join hands to transport the Caspian oil and natural gas
to the European markets.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and the United States signed a memorandum of
understanding on cooperation on energy issues during Yilmaz's
visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz held talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton and other
senior officials on bilateral and international issues.
</P>
<P>
A political consultation mechanism which deals with bilateral,
regional and international issues has been set up between the
two foreign ministries, Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's visit to Washington came following the European
Union (EU) announcement that Turkey would not be included in the
present EU enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the Turkish government hopes that
the Clinton administration would exert pressure on the EU on
Turkey's membership bid.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
has been a close ally of the United States in the Middle
East. 
</P>
