<HEADLINE> Somali Factions Sign Declaration of Principles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Warring factions of Somalia
today signed their most comprehensive ever peace deal to end the
six-year-old conflicts among them.
</P>
<P>
The power-sharing Somali Declaration of Principles signed here
also envisages the setting up of a federal government.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, signed by leaders of the two most powerful
factions, namely Hussein Mohammed Aidid from the Somali National
Alliance, and Ali Mahdi Mohammed from the 26-faction National
Salvation Council, calls for Somalia's independence, integrity and
security and the formation of a federal government.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony at Egypt's Foreign Ministry was attended
by Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid and a representative of the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed to hold a National Reconciliation Conference
in the Somali central city of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
The 465-member conference, which will be the biggest gathering
of the factions in years, is supposed to set up a 13-member
presidential council to select a president and a prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Somali faction leaders began talks on November 12 to try to
find a solution to their conflicts.
</P>
<P>
If the declaration works, it will help form the first central
government in Somalia since the 1991 ouster of the late president
Mohamed Siad Barre.
</P>
<P>
Since then Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected
by faction leaders to fight to expand their turfs. The factional
fighting, combined with a 1992 famine, has claimed about 300,000
lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
