<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: 1997 - a Gloomy Year for Thailand (1)  by Yu Zuncheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Thailand got a "black"
Christmas present this year: its foreign currency credit rating
was downgraded from Baa3 to Ba1.
</P>
<P>
The new rating announced Monday by U.S.-based international
rating agency Moody's Investors Service means that Thailand's
foreign currency ceiling for bonds and notes is lowered to junk
bond status.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to reduce inflows of foreign capital into
the country and limit the chances of Thai banks and finance
companies to raise funds from foreign sources, prolonging the
country's liquidity crunch.
</P>
<P>
Although the downgrading was not something unexpected, its
timing will certainly make Thailand's money market and stock
exchange more bearish towards the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the outgoing year, things have been moving from bad to worse
on the economic front,
</P>
<P>
First, the property market showed signs of severe stagnation
because of a massive oversupply of office, business and housing
space. Property developers were unable to sell their buildings to
pay their debts which they had borrowed from banks and finance
companies.
</P>
<P>
Real estate developers' insolvency has caused grave liquidity
crunch to banks, in particular finance companies. In the early
1990s, when property development was booming, many financial
institutions lent money to developers of risky projects because of
the attraction of high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Liquidity problems in the financial sector led to the
suspension of 58 finance companies in June and August by the
administration of Chavalit Yongchaiyudh. The move affected the
livelihood and interests of thousands of white-collar employees
and depositors and clients.
</P>
<P>
Second, when foreign money speculators launched repeated
attacks on the weakening Thai currency, the Chavalit government
did not take any action early enough to prevent the assaults.
</P>
<P>
The Chavalit cabinet, which was forced to resign last month due
to failure to solve the country's intricate economic problems, was
much blamed for two blunders.
</P>
<P>
One mistake was that it allowed the central bank to spend more
than 430 billion baht (about 16.86 billion U.S. dollars) of public
money early this year to bail out, in vain, the struggling private
finance companies.
</P>
<P>
Of the 58 suspended finance companies, 56 were proved hopeless
and were ordered early this month to close down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: 1997 - a Gloomy Year for Thailand (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another big mistake the Chavalit administration made was that
it failed to monitor the central bank's operation, which resulted
in the loss of 23.4 billion dollars in foreign reserves to defend
the baht, also to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, on July 2, the government had to announce that
the baht was allowed to float and find its own value against major
foreign currencies on the market.
</P>
<P>
But the floatation was too late, financial analysts said. If
the baht had been floated eight months earlier, the country could
have saved 40 billion dollars in international reserves and may
not have needed to seek assistance, under very strict conditions,
from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which agreed in August
to arrange a 17.2 billion dollar bailout package for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
From August when IMF assistance was requested, Thailand will
need to draw 9 billion dollars from the package by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Since Chuan Leekpai became the new prime minister last month,
because of international and domestic factors, things have not
improved much: the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index has kept
falling, and the baht further depreciated.
</P>
<P>
The SET index fell about 50 percent from the beginning of the
year to hover around 370 points this week. And by Monday, the baht
had lost 78 percent of its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Many companies have been shut down; factories have closed;
workers have been laid off; production costs and consumer prices
have soared.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, which is known as "the land of smiles," the
grinning will not be natural as the new year is drawing near.
</P>
<P>
Chuan Leekpai has promised to the nation that despite the
negative elements, the overall economic situation will begin to
improve in the second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
He may have reasons to say so: the depreciated baht is expected
to help boost exports and attract more foreign tourists; the IMF
fund will help strengthen the country's foreign reserves and
restructure the financial and industrial sectors; austerity
measures have been adopted; the government budget has been greatly
axed and many short-term foreign debts have been rolled over.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Chuan Leekpai and his party appear to be more
popular with the public, for their better images and stronger team
to tackle economic woes.
</P>
<P>
But given the present situation, the Chuan administration has a
rough way to go before confidence is restored in the local
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Establish Investment/Fund-raising System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China will place priority on
restructuring its investment and fund-raising system in 1998, as
well as on establishing internationally accepted system which
accords with the socialist market economy and separates the
functions of government from that of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Haoruo, vice-minister of the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy, made the remarks today during the
ongoing national economic restructuring conference.
</P>
<P>
The central government will further define the responsibilities
of governments, enterprises and banks in the projected system,
establish financial risk prevention mechanisms, cultivate the
capital market, allow more enterprises the right to raise funds
directly from society, and improve government macro-control and
administration over investment and fund-raising activities,
according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
China continues to lag behind in reform of its investment and
fund-raising system. Therefore, Chinese leaders consider
establishing a system in this regard, which separates the
functions of government from that of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Henceforth, governments at all levels will mainly invest in
public welfare projects and infrastructure, but not in competitive
projects under most circumstances, said Zhang, adding that
government-funded projects must be financed by noncommercial banks
or state-owned investment companies in the form of holding shares.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises will be the major investors in competitive
projects, and will be responsible for feasibility studies,
fund-raising, construction, and operations. Enterprises will be
required to apply for bank loans or obtain funding directly from
the capital market.
</P>
<P>
Banks will conduct investment assessments, make ensuing
decisions and bear risk, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Governments at various levels will divert a certain portion of
state capital from competitive projects and infrastructure to the
projects in public welfare, science, technology, and
education. Non-governmental projects will need no approval of but
registration with governments.
</P>
<P>
Efforts must be made to promote the major investor system and
invite consortia of major investors for projects.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that industrial policies and market information will
guide investment projects, and that governments at various
levels will regularly publish lists of which projects they are
encouraging, permitting, limiting, or prohibiting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
