<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls on UN to Lift Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz today called on the U.N. Security Council to lift the
sanctions imposed on Iraq immediately, Iraq News Agency (INA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
This was Iraq's first reaction to a Security Council statement
passed Monday, which urged Iraq to fully cooperate with the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction and allow arms inspectors to
enter any sites at any time.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the statement reflected once again the blackmail
exercised by the U.S. with the aim of inducing the council to
adopt unobjective and unbalanced attitudes.
</P>
<P>
He accused Washington of seeking to divert attention from the
essential issue, namely lifting the embargo laid on Iraq, to a
minor issue forced by it in collaboration with some elements of
the U.N. arms inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
Following UNSCOM's Chairman Richard Butler's recent visit to
Baghdad, Aziz said, American inspector Scott Ritter made over the
past few days 14 inspections of a number of sites, including some
previously inspected sites, without finding anything banned.
</P>
<P>
This exposed the falsehood of the UNSCOM's allegations that
Iraq conceals banned weapons, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi deputy prime minister called on the Security Council
to ask the UNSCOM about the source of its information which he
described as "trivial and false."
</P>
<P>
He accused the United States of dominating the UNSCOM, saying
that the commission has been turned into a U.S. instrumentality
serving sheer U.S. political ends.
</P>
<P>
Aziz urged the Security Council to adopt a balanced and
objective stance conducive to the immediate end of the embargo
imposed on Iraq for over seven years now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
