<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Talks About Ties With Non-Communist Parties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, who is
General Secretary of the Communist Party of China (CPC), in a
meeting with leaders of China's non-Communist Parties this
afternoon, said that the the CPC will continue to have long-term
co-operation with these democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was for newly-elected leaders of the country's
eight non-Communist parties and a federation and their
predecessors. These are the Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese
Kuomintang, the China Democratic League, the China democratic
National Construction Association, the China Association for
Promoting Democracy, the Chinese Peasants and Workers Democratic
Party, the China Zhi Gong Party (Public Interest Party), the Jiu
San (September 3) Society, the Taiwan Democratic Self-Government
League, and the All China Federation of Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the Chinese would not have achieveed national
independence, liberation, or socialist victory without the
leadership of the CPC. But he emphasized as well that without
multi-party co-operation under the leadership of the CPC, the
solidarity of all patriotic and progressive forces would be
impossible.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party co-operation and political consultation under
CPC leadership is the country's basic political system, he said,
and the CPC's leading position among all parties was established
during the historical process of the Chinese revolution and
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
