<HEADLINE> Israeli Ministers Take Inspection Tour of West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet ministers
led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took a helicopter tour
of the West Bank today to review first-hand issues connected with
further redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy and Agriculture Minister Rafael
Eitan boycotted the tour for different reasons. National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, who has presented his map
on the further redeployment and final settlement with the
Palestinians, served the tour guide.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, accompanied by senior army officers, flew in a
helicopter over the Jerusalem area, the Green Line (1949
armistice line) area and other strategic areas in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai showed the ministers areas
demarcated by his two maps presented to the cabinet, one on
Israeli military red lines and the other on Israeli national
interests.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret over boycott of the tour by Eitan who
protested what he called "political involvement" of the army in
drawing up a map on the further redeployment and permanent
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu sided with Mordechai in countering Eitan's accusation
of the defense establishment for its role in drawing up the map. He
said the army only provided professional advice on the issues.
</P>
<P>
During the tour, Sharon complained about outside pressure on
Israel to complete drawing up the map by January 15. He noted that
such crucial issues for Israel should not be dealt with haste.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to the United States which has
demanded the Israeli government to come out with a credible
decision as soon as possible in order to advance the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sharon and Mordechai differed on the size of two planned
security zones to be built along the Green Line and the Jordan
Valley, which are designed to protect Israel's future
safety. Mordechai, supported by Levy, favors reducing the width
of the security zones in order to avoid rejection by the
Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, the ministerial committee, which comprises
Netanyahu, Mordechai, Levy and Sharon, reconvened to further
discuss the remaining issues concerning the further redeployment
and permanent talks. The committee has already held four
sessions, but failed to reach a final solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
