<HEADLINE> Overseas-Based Chinese Companies Urged to Expand Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-based Shenzhen
businesses were urged today to take an active part in the
international economic cooperation and market competition for the
sake of the city.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, next to Hong Kong, is the country's first special
economic zone and the city today called a conference on the work
of its overseas-based businesses.
</P>
<P>
This means that overseas-based companies should engage more in
international co-operation and market competition to speed up
economic development in this south China city, which will select
as many as eight large pilot companies to develop multinational
business and give them preferential treatment in funding,
export quotas, and other aspects.
</P>
<P>
The city will also overhaul poorly-run overseas-based
companies, closing down those in the red.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has 212 overseas-based companies in 32 countries, that
are engaged in trade, industry, transport, real estate, tourism,
finance, and consultation.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Shenzhen's businesses have opened companies in
emerging markets in Africa, the Common Wealth of Independent
States, South America, and Eastern Europe, to promote the export
of technology, equipment, and other products.
</P>
<P>
A local official predicts that it will have 43.3 billion US
dollars worth of trade this year, 11 percent more than last year,
or one-seventh of China's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
