<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreigners Confident About Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners in Hong Kong are
satisfied with the current situation and confident in the future
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half a year after it returned to China on July 1, Hong
Kong is still running as usual, foreign businessmen, diplomats,
scholars and journalists said in their interviews with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
A representative of a major Japanese skin-care products
producer said that he likes to work in Hong Kong although there
exists keen competition among world known brands here.
</P>
<P>
Satoshi Hirota, chief representative of Japan's Shiseido
Company Limited, said that Hong Kong offers the fairest
competition environment in the world.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's economy is as free as it was before, Hirota said.
Neither the collapse of Yaohan nor the expansion of Shiseido in
Hong Kong has anything to do with the handover, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hirota's view was shared by many foreign businessmen in Hong
Kong. Most of the member companies of the American Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong (AmCham) plan to expand their business.
</P>
<P>
A recent AmCham Business Confidence Survey reflected a positive
outlook for the SAR's business environment against the background
of recent financial turbulence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Douglas Henk, chairman of the AmCham, said that the high-level
confidence is directly related to the smooth transition and
political stability, sound economic fundamentals, and an overall
improvement in U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
He said there are five favorable factors of doing business in
Hong Kong -- geographic location, communications network,
infrastructure, free port and taxation.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss people and enterprises express their strong
confidence in the future of Hong Kong in another way.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Swiss Consulate-General in Hong Kong organized
a month-long promotion entitled "Switzerland Greets Hong Kong,"
which showed the Hong Kong people Switzerland's business,
tourism, culture, gastronomy, arts and music.
</P>
<P>
Rolf Bodenmuller, Switzerland's consul-general to Hong Kong,
said that the current situation in Hong Kong is much better than
what people had expected nearly half a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Both Henk and Bodenmuller, who have been in Hong Kong for 11
and three years respectively, said they saw no sign of
interference from Beijing in the operation of the government of
the SAR and people in Hong Kong are still leading their lives in
the way they are used to.
</P>
<P>
They are confident about Hong Kong's prospect though they
predicted that Hong Kong's stock market will continue to be
volatile for a period of time.
</P>
<P>
Michael Degolyer, an American scholar at the Hong Kong Baptist
University, held similar views. He said that in the recent
regional financial turmoil, Hong Kong has done much better than
other Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
Degolyer said that the good performance against the backdrop of
the regional jitters should be owed to a good system Hong Kong has
built up.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's system is a reforming system. Problems arise and
Hong Kong learns to solve the problems. This is the proper way of
doing things," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He was excited about the prospects of Hong Kong: "China is set
to grow and Hong Kong has a position of growth leadership in
China's economic development."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreigners Confident About Hong Kong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
David Dodwell, who co-authored the influential book "The Hong
Kong Advantage" before Hong Kong's historic handover, said that
the recent Asia financial turmoil illustrated just how flexible
Hong Kong's economy is.
</P>
<P>
"It takes shocks very directly, deals with the shocks, absorbs
the shocks and repositions to where it's on. Much more quickly
than the other economies do," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The convincible study of the book "The Hong Kong Advantage"
dispersed doomsday myth that "Hong Kong is over." As the book
points out, Hong Kong's core strength lies in its immense
flexibility, a wide spread of economic activities, and a wide
spectrum of markets.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is luckily placed to have good strong business links
with the Chinese mainland to give it an extra area of business
activities to keep the economy robust," he reiterated a unique
advantage mentioned in the book.
</P>
<P>
Ruth Hayhoe, director of the Hong Kong Institute of Education,
looked at Hong Kong's return to China from a different angle.
</P>
<P>
Hayhoe, a Canadian who came to Hong Kong 30 years ago, said
that Hong Kong's young people now have a new opportunity to get to
know the remarkable civilization of China after Hong Kong returned
to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In the past the people in Hong Kong were largely restricted to
a small place with no national identity and they have a very
interesting task now to redevelop their identity, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that Hong Kong would have a very positive future
because it has demonstrated the economic and social vitality that
can result from an effective integration of aspects of Western and
Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Sinclair, a columnist for the South China Morning Post,
said that Hong Kong's social outlook is good because Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa and his colleagues are determined to make
life better for the average person.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair, who was born in New Zealand and came to Hong Kong in
1968, said that the determination and efficiency with which the
government officials have shown they will keep the peg with the
U.S. dollar has been very effective in stopping the economy from
suffering more.
</P>
<P>
"We have a marvelous team in our government and civil service,
all of them dedicated to making sure Hong Kong remains a wonderful
place to live," said Sinclair, who got his permanent Identity Card
of the HKSAR last month.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair said he has decided to spend the rest of his life in
Hong Kong because there is a good future for his family and
himself here.
</P>
<P>
However, not all the foreigners want to stay longer in Hong
Kong after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Shaver, a photographer of the Agence France-Presse
(AFP) Hong Kong bureau, who came to Hong Kong three years ago for
the handover, said that he has decided to leave Hong Kong because
the situation in Hong Kong is too stable to make any news.
</P>
<P>
Being stable is good for citizens and businessmen but not so
good for journalists, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
