<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Minister Criticizes Investment Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Agriculture Minister
Issa Kalantari has urged investment in the country's relatively
backward agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
Today's local daily Hamshahri quoted Kalantari as saying at a
ceremony for model farmers Monday that investment in the sector
showed a drop of 2.7 percent than that of eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the country's investors did not
involve in the agricultural sector effectively and conditioned
their investment in the sector on receipt of subsidies and credit
facilities from the government.
</P>
<P>
No one has the intention to put his investment on agriculture
unless the government pledges to compensate for half of the
losses, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He termed the situation of investment in agriculture as "very
serious," saying that because of shortage of necessary investment,
only one fifth of the country's tractor-manufacturing capacities
are in use, the aqueducts can not be revived and the drainage
system can not be put to use.
</P>
<P>
So it is necessary for the government and parliament to take
measures to ensure the security of the investment in the sector,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Ministry is determined to improve the quality
and quantity of crops, he added.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural output constitutes about 30 percent of the gross
domestic product and only meets about 60 percent of the needs of
food in the country. About 40 percent of the country's 67 million
population are involved in agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
