<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday urged Bosnian leaders in
Sarajevo to do their part in creating peace in their war-ravaged
country. He then visited a military base in Tuzla and praised
American soldiers for their role as peacekeepers in an ongoing
mission which he intends to extend.
</P>
<P>
-- A new survey suggested that, despite the exhortations of
President Vaclav Havel, fewer than half of Czechs surveyed support
NATO membership for their country. The results, described by a
Clinton Administration official as "not helpful," showed 42.8
percent of citizens supporting membership in the western alliance,
26.7 percent opposed and the remaining 30.5 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Formerly classified film showing a parachutist with a
so-called Special Atomic Demolition Munition was among formerly
classified material concerning atomic weapons, including hundreds
of thousands of pages of documents, released Monday by Energy
Secretary Federico Pena as part of a Clinton Administration program
announced four years ago to introduce greater openness on atomic
matters.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Federal agents have arrested the president of a small
southern garment-manufacturing firm on alien-smuggling charges
after breaking up a ring that recruited workers inside Mexico,
moved them illegally across the U.S. border and delivered them to
factories in Georgia and Alabama, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The Security Council demanded that Iraq allow U.N. arms
inspectors into all suspected weapons sites, saying failure to do
so was "unacceptable." The statement mentioned no measures to
force Baghdad to allow inspections of Saddam Hussein's palaces.
Separately, Persian Gulf nations urged Iraq to comply with
inspections.
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey ordered a Greek diplomatic aide expelled on suspicion
of espionage, and Athens said it was responding in kind, further
worsening relations between the two NATO members. Separately,
Turkey, Israel and the U.S. said they would hold joint naval
exercises, their first, off Israel next month. 
</P>
