<HEADLINE> Philippine President Condemns Leftist Rebels' Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos Tuesday accused leftist rebels of violating their own
ceasefire declaration and urged them to release 22 hostages they
have taken.
</P>
<P>
Ramos was reacting to the raids conducted by the New People's
Army (NPA) recently in two remote villages in the southern city of
Davao.
</P>
<P>
He called on the NPA "to respect their own ceasefire
declaration" and "not let the Christmas season be spoiled by their
offensive operations."
</P>
<P>
NPA guerrillas attacked two villages in Paquibato district,
some 60 kilometers from Davao city, and seized 22 members of the
Civilian Armed Force Geographical Unit last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The NPA has declared a ceasefire during the Christmas season
and the military has also announced suspension of military
operation for 30 days during the Christmas holiday.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the militiamen were in their localities observing
the ceasefire when they were seized by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Ramos ordered Arnulfo Acedera, chief of staff of the Armed
Forces of the Philippines, to pursue the rebels and "to make sure
that the communities are safe in that area."
</P>
<P>
"Apparently, this is the attack by the NPA group that did not
respect their own unilateral ceasefire," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The NPA has fought the government for more than three decades
and still has a presence in many hinterland areas in the country.
</P>
