<HEADLINE> hke - German Real Estate Giant Sentenced Six Years' Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- German real estate tycoon Juergen
Schneider was sentenced by a Frankfurt court to six years and nine
months in prison Tuesday for fraud leading to the biggest real
estate bankruptcy in postwar Germany.
</P>
<P>
The term was exactly one year less than what the prosecution
had demanded last week for Schneider, 63, who was found guilty of
five counts of serious fraud.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the milder verdict, the judge said that Schneider's
conduct had been partly provoked and facilitated by the
"incredible negligence" of the country's lending institutions.
</P>
<P>
Schneider was found presenting faked documents to seek bank
loans before the multi-billion U.S. dollar collapse of his company
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the five cases of fraud he was charged with, Schneider
obtained 165 million marks (93 million dollars) in credits.
</P>
<P>
At the height of his business, Schneider was involved in
prime-location real estate projects in 14 cities, building luxury
hotels, office buildings and shopping arcades. His company based
near Frankfurt once owned 168 real estate properties.
</P>
<P>
Most of the assets has been sold, leaving some 2.6 billion mark
of the total 5.4 billion mark debts uncovered when Schneider and
his wife Claudia suddenly went missing in April 1994.
</P>
<P>
They were found living in Florida, the United States, 13 months
later and were extradited to Germany in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Besides the fraud case, Schneider and his wife are also facing
possible separate legal proceedings for fraudulent bankruptcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
