<HEADLINE> Russian Plane Barred from Entering Iraq Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A much-expected Russian
attempt to break the flight ban on Iraq has been thwarted by the
Iranian authorities, reliable Iraqi sources told Xinhua News
Agency today.
</P>
<P>
A airplane chartered by the Russian Liberal Democratic Party
and bound for Baghdad was barred by Iran from entering Iraq
through Iran's airspace.
</P>
<P>
The plane was due to arrive at the Saddam International Airport
Sunday with 20 LDP representatives in the State Duma (lower house
of the parliament) and some specialists on board.
</P>
<P>
Saad Qassem Hamoudi, chairman of the Arab and International
Relations Committee of Iraq's National Assembly (parliament), was
awaiting the plane's arrival Monday at the airport.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters the Russian flight came on an initiative made
by LDP leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky during his visit to Baghdad
early this month.
</P>
<P>
Hamoudi described the Russian flight as a "courageous and bold"
move worth appreciation, and as a practical break of the embargo
laid on Iraq for seven years.
</P>
<P>
Commercial flights are banned to and from Iraq except with
U.N. approval. Hamoudi said that instead of asking the U.N. for
approval of the flight, the Russian party applied to Iran and
Azerbaijan, whose airspaces the plane would pass through, for
approval.
</P>
<P>
He said the plane, which belongs to a Russian non-governmental
company, was due to leave Russia on December 19 but its flight was
delayed because of the need to get approvals from Iran and
Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Zhirinovsky had strongly denounced the U.N. embargo
during his visit to Baghdad, affirming that his party stands by
the Iraqi people who are suffering from the sanctions imposed
following Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi sources, the Russian airplane is not
likely to arrive at the Saddam International Airport today, and it
is still unknown whether the plane is still in Iran or it has
returned to Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
