<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cairo Declaration Wins Widespread Support in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Cairo Declaration
reached by the main Somali factions last night has won widespread
support among the social groups and people in the streets of
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohamed Moallim Hassan, the most prominent religious
leader in Somalia has welcomed the agreement with happiness and
joy, considering the results of the six-week talks as "the first
light of peace for Somalia."
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hassan further said he would remind the factions that
all agreements should be based on the Islamic law or Sharia.
</P>
<P>
People of Mogadishu were today talking much about the
agreement. Newspapers gave a huge coverage to the historic event
in Cairo last night.
</P>
<P>
Xog-Ogaal Daily described the accord as "a great victory" via
unforgettable negotiations. Another weekly, The Horn of Africa,
which supports Hussein Mohamed Aidid, ran an article entitled
"you better be provoked instead of provoking," -- a Somali
proverb meaning that one should retreat from his desires for the
common good.
</P>
<P>
Hawo Mohamed Ossoble, chairlady of the Mogadishu-based Somali
Women's Democratic Organization, said the Somali mothers are
happy and confident of the "agreement of principles" issued in
Cairo last night.
</P>
<P>
"We'll get ready for the participation of the meeting in mid
February in Baidoa," she said, calling on the faction leaders not
to ignore the role of the Somali women in future administration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some of the political leaders in Mogadishu have
expressed their strong support to the outcome of the meeting. For
example, the Secretary General of Osman Ali Atto's faction, Abdi
Hassan Awale Qeybdid, has also labeled the meeting as a gorgeous
one.
</P>
<P>
Qeybdid thanked the Egyptian government for its "brotherhood"
concern over the Somali crises. Cairo mediated among the factions
and sponsored the meeting to achieve reconciliation in Somalia
which is one of the Arab League members.
</P>
<P>
"I see this agreement as a solution in regaining the dignity
of Somalia," said the Information Secretary of Ali Mahdi's
faction, Hussein Sheikh Ahmed Kadare. "I don't believe that any
reasoning mind would oppose this agreement," he added, "it's a
bridge for a better future."
</P>
<P>
The Cairo Agreement demands that a government with a 13-member
presidential council be formed with a president, and a prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed upon the formation of a 189-member
constituent assembly and an independent judicial system.
</P>
<P>
Although two Somali politicians have walked out of the meeting
in its last days, this agreement has the support of the vast
majority of Somalia. The quitters, General Adan Abdullahi Nur
Gabyow and Colonel Abdullahi Yussuf, were being represented by
their colleagues who signed the pact.
</P>
<P>
On February 15 next year, 465 delegates will go to the
southwestern town of Baidoa for a national reconciliation
conference where a future interim government will be announced, a
good final test for the faction leaders of Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
