<HEADLINE> China to Award Wildlife Protection Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The China Wildlife
Conservation Association (CWCA), the country's largest
non-governmental nature reserve organization, announced today that
it will grant awards to individuals who have made outstanding
contributions to China's wildlife protection efforts.
</P>
<P>
Recipients, both Chinese and foreign, who have worked at the
forefront of China's wildlife protection, including scientific
research, publicity and education and law enforcement, will
receive gold and silver medals.
</P>
<P>
The CWCA, established in 1983, currently has 40,000 members
throughout the nation. The organization has played a major role in
mobilizing social forces to join wildlife protection efforts, and
has sponsored a number of scientific research projects.
</P>
<P>
The CWCA has established cooperation ties with a number of
foreign countries and international organizations. Over the past
seven years, the organization has received a total of 5.55 million
yuan and 2.79 million US dollars in donations from both home and
abroad. 
