<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Industries Create More Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The "Survey Bulletin of China's Township Industrial Polluters",
jointly released by the National Environmental Protection Agency
(NEPA), the Ministry of Agriculture, the Ministry of Finance and
the State Statistical Bureau, points to the fact that township
industrial pollution has emerged a major problem in environmental
protection efforts and an important factor affecting the health
and well-being of Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"Steps must be taken, management must be strengthened, and
spending must be increased to improve the country's pollution
control capacity," according to the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin points out that China has more than 1.2 million
township industrial polluters, mainly in the non-metallic mineral
products, textile, food processing, metallic products, chemical
and machine-building sectors.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Shandong and Guangdong provinces have the
vast majority of developed township industries.
</P>
<P>
Said enterprises discharged 5.9 billion tons of wastewater in
1995, in the level of organic pollutants hitting 6.11 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In terms of industrial waste gas emissions, the volume of
sulphur dioxide was 4.41 million tons, the figure for smoke and dust
stood at 8.5 million tons, and suspended particles in the form of
industrial waste was over 13 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The level of solid wastes stood at 180 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of organic pollutants in wastewater, smoke and dust,
suspended particles from industrial waste and solid waste
discharged by the township businesses accounted for over 50
percent of the national total, according to the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
China carried out a township industrial polluter survey from
January 1996 to December 1997, the most extensive survey of its
kind in history. Data obtained the survey covering 1995 will be
used as a criterion for the country's pollution control program.
</P>
<P>
China plans, by the year 2000, to maintain major pollutant
emissions around levels for the year 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
