<HEADLINE> Australian Stock market Closes 2.2 Percent Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Healthy share price rises
across the board, led by the gold and resource sectors, pushed the
Australian stock market more than 2.2 percent higher Tuesday,
although volume was flat ahead of the Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index more than made up for Monday's 24.7
point loss, rising 55.5 points, or 2.2 percent, for a close of
2558.9. The gold index closed above the 1,000-point mark for the
first time since November 13.
</P>
<P>
"The gold index received a shot in the arm from the (gold miner)
Plutonic takeover bid (on Monday)," Shaw Stockbroking's Jack Moss
said.
</P>
<P>
Stronger offshore markets in New York and Hong Kong also
influenced Tuesday's performance, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Plutonic Resources was a stand-out performer in the wake of US
giant Homestake Mining Company's near 650 million US dollars bid
for the company.
</P>
<P>
Homestake's offer, which values Plutonic shares at 5.20
Australian dollars each, saw the stock jump 1.60 Australian
dollars to end at 4.40 Australian dollars as 6.8 million shares
changed hands. Its intra-day high was 4.556 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index surged 71.1 points, or 7.5 percent, to finish at
1,016.9.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trading in gold bullion closed at 291.55 US dollars an
ounce, up 1.75 US dollars on Monday's close of 289.80 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks also posted solid gains, with resources giant
BHP climbing 34 cents to 14.08 Australian dollars, global miner
Rio Tinto strengthening 47 to 17.27 Australian dollars, and mining
company WMC closing 16 cents firmer at 5.08 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The resources index rose 30.8 points or 2.85 percent to 1111.7,
and the industrial index followed in kind, moving up two percent,
or 87.5 points, to 4375.1.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a modest 273.58 million and worth 465.93
million US dollars. Rises easily outnumbered falls 662 to 369,
with 316 remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
Australia's most profitable bank, NAB, added 42 cents to 20.64
Australian dollars, ANZ bank bounced back 29 cents to 9.79
Australian dollars, and Westpac bank finished 23.1 cents better at
9.63 Australian dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
