<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Situation Remains Calm in Nigeria After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Nigeria
remains comparatively calm in the third day after the government
announcement of uncovering a coup attempt Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is calm in the country and everybody goes on
his duty normally," defense spokesman Godwin Ugbo said this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Uugbo promised to provide on a daily basis the latest
development in the investigation of the foiled coup involving
Nigeria's second man, Chief of General Staff Oladip Diya and 11
others.
</P>
<P>
according to the spokesman, a panel of security officers and
civilians is carrying out the investigation.
</P>
<P>
The Acting Director of Defense Information said that the
police has beefed up security throughout the country, but he
refuted allegations that heavily armed soldiers have been
deployed in barracks and other sensitive places.
</P>
<P>
The coup plot has become focus of talks among people in Lagos,
many of whom said the news came as shock to them.
</P>
<P>
"I was shocked when i heared it from the BBC Monday morning,"
said a driver in a Lagos car marketing company.
</P>
<P>
The driver said he could not understand why Diya, who as the
country's number two citizen is powerful and rich enough, would
do such thing.
</P>
<P>
A local newspaper correspondant shared the similar view,
saying that he was puzzled with the matter.
</P>
<P>
"Coup is a serious thing. The government would not play with
it. But why Diya did it since he should know the result quite
clearly," the reporter said.
</P>
<P>
For diplomats, they are busy with getting details of the
happening and analyzing its implications toward to the country's
on-going transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
But under the government's firm information control, what is
generally accepted among them at the moment is that the event
must be the result of struggle for power within the military
government.
</P>
<P>
To avoid misinformation of the public, Nigeria has tightened
control of information, according to the country's new Minister
of Information and Culture, Chief Ikeobasi Mokelu.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who was sworn in along with 32 other fellow
ministers five days ago, said on Monday that the government would
not tolerate any action capable of disturbing national security.
</P>
<P>
Making it clearer to journalists, Ugbo told them to be
cautious in their reports on the coup plot.
</P>
<P>
Quoting from foreign media without confirmation is unaccetable
especially when investigations are going on, said the
defense spokesman.
</P>
<P>
As to Anthony Onyearugbulem, the military administrator of
Ondo State in southwest Nigeria, civil servants in the state are
not allowed to comment on the alleged coup plot for subversion,
the Punch newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Describing it as "purely a military affair", the navy
commander threatened: "I will try you. I will crush you for
subservion, if you talk on what you don't know."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a top government officials at a meeting on Monday,
he also cautioned the state-owned media stations, urging them to
exercise restraint on airing people's views on the alleged coup
plot.
</P>
<P>
While some political parties rise to condemn the alleged coup
plot, human rights and pro-democracy groups are demanding for
more details of the event and fair, open trial.
</P>
<P>
The British High Commission (embassy) also echoed the demand,
saying that "it is important those arrested are treated in
accordance with due judicial process."  
</P>
