<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reactions Differ in S.Leone Concerning Nigeria's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Reactions by both Nigerians
and Sierra Leoneans to the announced coup plot in Nigeria
gathered momentum in Freetown today due to Nigeria's intensive
political involvement in Sierra Lwone's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 Nigerian troops are now in Sierra Leone and aided
by Nigerian air force Alfa jets and tanks, monitoring sanctions
and embargo imposed by west African leaders since July against
the military junta to return constitutional order to the deposed
civilian government by April next year.
</P>
<P>
"Abacha (the Nigerian head of state) is at it again to silence
all opposition to his one man, strong rule" said a Nigerian
trader, while a retired Sierra Leonean banker called the alleged
plot "a gimmick to divert attention from Nigeria's chronic
political and economic problems."
</P>
<P>
"The development is an attempt to forestall a return to
democratic rule according to Abacha's transitional program," said
a Freetown lawer.
</P>
<P>
Others said the development "is to throw dust into our eyes
while he (Abacha) goes on to snatch victory in next year's
presidential election as a civilian candidate."
</P>
<P>
A university lecturer back from a sabbatical at the University
of Lagos wonders whether "if the coup had succeeded, there would
have been an ECOMOG military build-up in Nigeria just like what
is currently happening in Sierra Leone ?"
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian foreign currency exchange dealer said he was
"totally disgusted" over the many coups and counter coups in
Nigeria and the "many military officers who would be facing the
firing squad or lengthy jail sentences" and wondered "what will
it all end up to."
</P>
<P>
Some Nigerians said frankly that "they would rather hold their
views privately fearing reprisals when they decide to return
home" while others shrugged their shoulders saying they are
"plainly not interested."
</P>
<P>
The military junta has so far not commented on the development
in Nigeria but the state run radio and TV continued to give the
news top priority.
</P>
<P>
The privately owned FM 103 radio station which is sympathetic
to the junta called the alleged plot "a forecast of doom to
Abacha's rule." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
