<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nonferrous Metals Industry Continues to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China's nonferrous metals
industry, the world's second largest in terms of output following
the United States, has had 15 consecutive years of growth.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released during the industry's national
conference held here today, China is expected to produce 5.3
million tons of 10 types of nonferrous metals in high demand,
including 1.05 million tons of copper, 600,000 tons of lead and
1.35 million tons of zinc.
</P>
<P>
Since May, subsidiaries of the China National Nonferrous Metals
Industry Corp., which operated in the red during the first four
months of the year, have reduced losses on a monthly basis,
according Yang Guang, assistant general manager of the
corporation. He also noted that the profitability of subsidiaries
has further improved.
</P>
<P>
The subsidiaries are expected to earn profits totaling 100
million yuan and pay taxes of over 2.7 billion yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that progress has been made in enterprises reform and
noted that three enterprises which were listed on the stock
exchange earlier this year raised a total of 2.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for the corporation's imports and exports for
the year to hit 1.8 billion US dollars, with exports ending the
year at 1.3 billion US dollars. The corporation won contracts for
18 overseas projects valued at 500 million US dollars during the
year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the corporation invested over 200 million yuan in
prospecting projects.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, its proven reserves of copper reached 300,000 tons;
bauxite 23.6 million tons; gold 40 tons; silver 1,246 tons; and
stibium 68,000 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
