<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Relief Funds Total 4.4 Billion Yuan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Central and local governments,
as well as various social circles, provided over 4.4 billion yuan
(about 530 million US dollars) in disaster relief funds during 1997,
according to the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 30-40 million people in areas struck by disasters
received assistance, according to Li Bengong, director of the
ministry's disaster relief department.
</P>
<P>
The central government appropriated 2.2 billion yuan for
disaster relief during 1997, with local governments providing 1.2
billion yuan, and people of various social circles donating cash and
materials valued at one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Li announced the figures at a conference of directors of
provincial civil affairs departments held in Chengdu, capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
When compared to previous years, China suffered from a
relatively moderate scale of disasters during 1997, with the most
serious problems occurring in areas suffering from drought.
</P>
<P>
Between July and September this year, more than a dozen
provinces, including Henan in central China, Shandong in east
China, and various provinces in north China suffered from the
worst droughts in decades.
</P>
<P>
Shandong's precipitation levels for last fall were the lowest
since 1904. Drought conditions were even worse in coastal cities
such as Yantai, Weihai, Qingdao and Rizhao, all of which witnessed
plummeting grain harvests and withering fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, saltwater encroached on the underground water
table creating saline conditions affecting the land and causing
heavy losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Relief Funds Total 4.4 Billion Yuan (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Local residents will most likely face a hard winter due to the
affects of meager autumn grain harvests," said Li.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be placed on disaster relief during the winter
season, according to Li. Central government disaster relief
allocations from November this year through March next year will
hit 710 million yuan, up 100 million yuan on last winter.
</P>
<P>
Earthquakes were yet another source of major disasters this
year, according to Li. Seven quakes measuring over six on the
Richter scale hit China during 1997, with the vast majority of
quakes occurring in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The central government allocated 82 million yuan in disaster
relief funds for Xinjiang during 1997, with over half of the
funds going to people living in areas struck by earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 300 million people throughout the country were
adversely affected by various kinds of disasters this
year. However, thanks to the efforts of governments at various
levels, people in disaster received timely and greatly appreciated
relief.
</P>
<P>
Over the next few months, civil affairs departments will place
priority on effectively distributing disaster relief funds in
order to ensure that local residents pass the winter season in
relative comfort, said Li.  
</P>
</TEXT>
