<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Sales in Australia Soar to Record level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Australia's car makers and
importers enjoyed boom times in 1997 as sales soared to record
levels.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, 655,871 new cars and commercial
vehicles had been retailed across Australia, up 10 percent
compared with the 595,834 units in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Even with only moderate demand in December the full year result
was likely to be somewhere between 710,000 and 720,000, exceeding
700,000 units for the first time, the Australian Associated Press
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ford Australia looked set to retain its market leading status
with a healthy lead by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
The company had sold 119,504 vehicles compared with 114,403 for
Toyota and 110,785 for Holden, a General Motor-owned local car
producer. Toyota was the only one in the big three local car
producers which enjoyed an increase in total sales volume.
</P>
<P>
Holden's fortunes improved dramatically in the final quarter
following the release of the new VT Commodore which was also
expected to be the nation's top seller.
</P>
<P>
The long-term future of Australia's four vehicle manufacturers
also received a significant boost this year with the federal
government finally deciding to place a freeze on tariff cuts on
imported cars.
</P>
<P>
In a somewhat surprising decision, Prime Minister John Howard
went against a majority recommendation from the Industry
Commission and decided in June to freeze tariffs on imported cars
from year 2000 to 2005.
</P>
<P>
Under the new arrangement, tariffs will continue to fall by 2.5
percent until they reach 15 percent at the turn of the century
when the freeze will be applied.
</P>
<P>
The tariffs will be lowered to 10 percent in 2005 when a
further review will take place.
</P>
<P>
Overall, vehicle and car component exports were expected to
grow to about 1.69 billion U.S. dollars compared with 1.36 billion
dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On the financial front, Australia's car makers also enjoyed
good times with Holden posting an after-tax profit of 157 million
dollars for 1996 and Ford 141 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Toyota did not release its results but was thought to have
enjoyed improved fortunes after several years in the red with its
manufacturing operations.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi plunged into a 39 million dollar loss last year
after a heavy investment for the launch of new model Magna, but
Managing Director Mike Quinn forecast a return to profitability
when the results for 1997 are released.
</P>
<P>
Of the leading importers, Hyundai was clearly the pick of the
bunch with sales jumping to 55,273 units by the end of November
compared with 46,103 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai's distribution company, Astre Automotive, also posted a
record after-tax profit of 22.23 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the good times may be over with the specter of falling
exchange rates set to end the honeymoon in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar slumped recently to a four-year low
against the U.S. dollar and also fell against other currencies
including the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
This prompted vehicle importers to warn of impending price
increases, something almost certain to turn away customers in the
coming 12 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
