<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Hold First Free Municipal Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's parliament has
decided to elect municipal council members and mayors through
nationwide free elections next April, instead of appointment
proposed by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star newspaper reported today that by a majority
vote, the parliament late Monday night rejected the government
bill to appoint municipal council members and approved to hold an
open municipal and mayoral elections across the country.
</P>
<P>
But this does not apply in south Lebanon, which is being
occupied by Israeli troops, and villages whose displaced residents
have not returned, according to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
This decision is an apparent blow to President Elias Hrawi and
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri government's support for a
controversial provision to appoint one-third of the councils,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
During the 1975-1990 civil war, thousands of Lebanese, mostly
the Christians, had to flee their villages to avoid the
fighting. About 500,000 have not been repatriated so far.
</P>
<P>
In this case, the president, a Maronite Catholic, favors
appointments under the pretext that the demographic change could
lead to drastic losses for the country's Christians in direct
public vote.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, a Sunni Muslim, agreed with the president,
stressing the appointment could preserve the country's sectarian
balance between Muslims and Christians, which has been established
since its independence in 1943.
</P>
<P>
But their position sparked strong criticism from members of
parliament and politicians, who argued that the appointment will
infringe on democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Calls for Mine-Clearing Policy in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Julio Mapote, coordinator for
the Mozambican Anti-Mine Campaign, has called for a national
policy for the humanitarian mission of land-mine clearance.
</P>
<P>
It is very important to make such a policy so as to prevent
some enterprises from seeking purely for commercial interests in
land mine clearing, he said.
</P>
<P>
The local paper Noticias today quoted Mapote as making the
statement here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Mapote, all contracts for land mine clearing
should be signed after taking into account the internal and
external interests. The venue for mine clearing should be
decided first by the Mozambicans, instead of foreigners, from
whom the money comes.
</P>
<P>
Mapote revealed that some companies and enterprises only
remove the mines out of economic interests. Take World Vision
for instance, it cleared mines in a certain region in Nampula
province, northern Mozambique so as to make developments in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Mozambican armed forces should regard
mine-clearing as a priority, although peace has already
materialized in the country," noted the coordinator.
</P>
<P>
He urged parliament to approve the Ottawa Agreement on mines
before next June and take measures to further implement the
accord.
</P>
<P>
About two million land mines had been planted in Mozambique
during its 16-year-long civil war. So far only 100,000 mines have
been removed.
</P>
<P>
In the process of mine-clearing, there have been conflicts
between foreign companies and Mozambican engineers over payment,
as a result, more often than not the latter were sacked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
