<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Consumer Price Inflation Eases in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The year-on-year rate of
increase for consumer price inflation in Hong Kong, as measured by
the Consumer Price Index (CPI)(A), was 5.1 percent in November,
lower than that of 5.5 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
The CPI(A) covers the largest percentage of Hong Kong's
households.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year rate of increase in the CPI(B), at 5.4 percent
in November, was also lower than that of 5.7 in October.
</P>
<P>
The corresponding rate of increase in the Hang Seng CPI was 5.9
percent in November, the same as the increase recorded in October.
</P>
<P>
The Composite CPI, which is compiled based on the combined
expenditure pattern of households covered by the three
sub-indices, showed a year-on-year increase of 5.4 percent in
November, lower than that of 5.7 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first 11 months of 1997 together, the increases in
the CPI(A) and CPI(B) both averaged at 5.8 percent over a year
earlier. The corresponding increases for the Hang Seng CPI and
Composite CPI were 6.1 percent and 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government had earlier revised down the forecast for this
year's consumer price inflation from 6.5 percent to 6 percent as
inflationary pressures continued to ease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
