<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Poland to Partially Abolish Visa requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Poland
signed an agreement here Tuesday to partially abolished visa
requirements easing travel between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would facilitate short-term visits to Poland by
Malaysians holding international, diplomatic, official and gratis
passports as well as emergency certificates, Secretary-General of
the Malaysian Foreign Ministry Abdul Kadir Mohamad said at the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Poles holding ordinary, diplomatic, official
passports and Sailor's Books or Consular passports could now visit
Malaysia as a matter of routine, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that however, those seeking employment and other paid
activities, coming for studies and professional training or
seeking permanent residence would have to obtain visa.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was an important step towards enhancing relations
between Malaysia and Poland, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
