<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam State Bank to Stablize Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Vietnam (SBV)
will do its best to constrain the fluctuation of exchange rates
when necessary, said Do Que Luong, the SBV's acting governor.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the Vietnamese dong (VND) against the
U.S. dollar has climbed high over the past few days on the black
market, exceeding the ceiling rate permitted by the SBV by 8-10
percent.
</P>
<P>
The current exchange rate at Vietcombank (Vietnam Commercial
Bank) is 12,293 VND per dollar. However, on the free market the
rate last saturday soared to 13,650 VND in Hanoi and 13,450 VND
per dollar in Ho Chi Minh city.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government will adjust the exchange market
within a permissible frame which is advantageous to the national
economy, Luong said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, the SBV has made continued
efforts to adjust the exchange rate of the vietnamese dong
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
In Mid-October, the SBV widened the band from plus or minus 5
percent of the official rate, fixed by the SBV, to 10 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Luong said since the exchange volume on the free market is just
about one-tenth of that of the inter-bank, there was no need to
worry about the fluctuations of exchange rates on the free market
since they are "not real."
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reasons for the greenback's price hike, Luong
said a segment of the population was worried about a possible
depreciation of the dong and tried to speculate the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The acting governor added that the devaluation of gold on the
world market also leads a lower value of the dong against the
dollar. Speculators, including some enterprises, have hoarded the
greenback to buy smuggled gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
