<HEADLINE> India Opens Highway Construction to Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- India's Surface Transport
Secretary Yogendra Narain said Tuesday that the central government
has opened the construction of the entire 35,000 kilometer
national highway to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a conference on transport infrastructure organized
by the Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) here, he said this
was a massive program for contractors and BOT (build, operate and
transfer) operators.
</P>
<P>
He added that such a program would give a fillip to the
country's economy and provide large-scale employment.
</P>
<P>
India's national highway is owned by the government and managed
by the state-owned National Highway Authority. With the
introduction of economic reforms in the country, infrastructure
including the national highway has become more and more important
in the economic development of the country. The National Highway
Authority itself could not cope with the emerging situation due to
shortage of money.
</P>
<P>
The government is also considering developing expressways of
the American pattern and it has already given approval for
construction of two expressways in the country, the secretary
said.
</P>
<P>
While the Asian Development Bank has agreed to fund the
Mumbai-Baroda expressway, the Finance Ministry has gained adequate
support for another planned expressway between Kanpur and Agra, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
