<HEADLINE> ASEAN Adopts Action Plan to Tackle Regional Haze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Environment ministers from
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) formally
adopted an action plan here on Tuesday to help tackle the regional
haze problem.
</P>
<P>
Called the Regional Haze Action Plan, it sets out a concrete
cooperative program to address the haze problem caused by land and
forest fires. The plan was announced by Singapore Environment
Minister Yeo Cheow Tong at the end of the two-day ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting on Haze.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said that the plan will focus joint efforts on three
fronts, namely forest fire prevention, strengthening regional fire
fighting capability, and developing fire monitoring mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
These efforts will be spearheaded by Malaysia, Indonesia and
Singapore respectively. The ASEAN member countries also include
Thailand, the Philippines, Brunei, Vietnam, Myanmar, and Laos.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore minister said that the plan adopted demonstrated
ASEAN's firm commitment to prevent a recurrence of the haze
problem.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Environment Minister Sarwono Kusumatatmadja also
pledged that efforts in his country will be stepped up to prevent
indiscriminate burning by companies.
</P>
<P>
To this end, he said that he will propose what is called "a
monitorium" on the setting up of new palm oil plantations and will
impose stricter penalties on those who flout environmental laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
