<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Tobacco Earnings Expected to Hit Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Annual earnings for
Tanzanian tobacco are expected to reach a record of 60 million US
dollars in 1997, The Guardian said today.
</P>
<P>
Earnings were based on 1997 production estimates of 42.041
million kilograms of Virginia Flue Cured (VFC) tobacco and 9.054
million kgs of Dark Fire Cured (DFC) tobacco, the paper quoted
Frank Urio, Leaf Development Manager of the Tanzania Tobacco
Board (TTB), as saying.
</P>
<P>
Production in 1996 stood at 27.101 million kgs of VFC and
8.279 million kgs of DFC worth 56 million US dollars. Production
in 1995 was 23.415 million kgs of VFC tobacco and 5.183 million
kgs of DFC.
</P>
<P>
Urio believed that prospects for continuing strong growth in
the tobacco sector are excellent.
</P>
<P>
The massive jump in production from 1996 to 1997 reflects the
impact of private sector investment in Tanzania's tobacco
industry liberalized in 1995, Urio said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's three main tobacco buyers -- Universal Leaf
Tobacco, Diamond Leaf Tobacco and Standard Commercial Tobacco
Leaf -- are all U.S.- registered and listed on the New York stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
"Since market liberalization of the tobacco trade, we have
seen an era of closer cooperation between tobacco growers and
leaf dealers," Urio said, adding "This arrangement has given
growers assistance in receiving inputs in the right quantity and
right time."
</P>
<P>
As a result of liberalization, growers, mostly small holder
farmers, can sell their crop at optimum prices with prompt
payment guaranteed. Given good weather, production for 1998 was
forecast at 43 million kgs of VFC tobacco, he said.
</P>
<P>
VFC tobacco accounts for about 80 percent of total tobacco
grown in Tanzania, mostly in the central Tabora region, with the
balance made up by DFC.
</P>
<P>
According to Urio, the ongoing farmer education programs
stressed improved crop management which is aimed at obtaining
higher yields.
</P>
<P>
"Despite increases in production there are still a lot of
areas to be improved -- extended acreage is one. We (TTB) think
yields per acre could be increased. This is one area to be
addressed because yields are very low," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, one tobacco harvest per year normally takes place
from mid January to April.
</P>
<P>
The main harvest months are February and March. Tobacco
planting is normally from mid-November to mid-March. The
industry, including farmers and process workers, numbers around
440,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Reform of Fund-Raising Mix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China will take effective
measures to expand its capital market during 1998, and will
encourage more enterprises to raise funds on the market in order
to meet the needs of ongoing state enterprise reform and adjust
the national economic structure.
</P>
<P>
"China expects to achieve new breakthroughs in expanding its
capital market during 1998," according to Zhang Haoruo, vice
minister of the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy. Zhang made the remarks during a national conference on
economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The measures will include the selection of more efficient
enterprises to be listed on the stock market, expansion of the
issue quota for convertible bonds, permission of qualified
enterprises to issue financial bonds overseas, acceleration of the
formulation of regulations on investment funds, and pursuance of
conventional international fund-raising methods, according to
Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that reform of the fund-raising mix continues to
lag behind and pointed out that indirect financing other than bank
loans still plays a major role in direct funding, as well as in
pooling funds by issuing stocks and bonds, and establishing
investment funds.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 800 Chinese companies are
currently listed on the nation's stock markets. During the
January-November period alone, 185 Chinese companies issued A
shares, 15 companies issued B shares targeted at foreign
investors, and 19 firms gained listings on overseas stock
market. The various forms of stock issues raised a total of 147.5
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that accelerated expansion of the Chinese stock
market is an inevitable trend manifested by the 30 billion yuan
stock issue quota for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also noted that China will strictly adhere to the related
procedures for listed companies, explore new approaches for
listing state-owned shares and legal person shares, and will
promote the transfer of stock rights in non-listed companies.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that China will actively and steadily develop a
corporate bond market, and will issue additional convertible
bonds, while tightening supervision over the issuance, conversion
and redemption of related bonds.
</P>
<P>
He called for the redoubling of efforts to implement the
regulations on managing securities investment funds and for
continuing experiments in establishing investment funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
