<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opposes ICJ's Report on Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is in
resolute opposition to the act of the International Commission of
Jurists (ICJ) to interfere in China's internal affairs by issuing
a report on Tibet, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Tang Guoqiang told a press conference this afternoon
that the authors of the report are extremely ignorant of the
history and present state of Tibet. It is apparent that they are
also extremely ignorant of the norms of international relations
and the international law, he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Tibet has been an inalienable part of China since
ancient times and Tibetan affairs are purely China's internal
affairs, he said that no international organization has the right
to put its hands on or meddle in these affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tang stressed that the ICJ's report overlooks the territorial
sovereignty of China by advocating Tibet's self-determination and
accusing China of human rights violation in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly opposed to this," he said.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the ICJ should respect the general purpose and
principles of the Charter of the United Nations and stop such
activities of interfering in China's internal affairs, Tang said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
