<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Chief Justice Sajjad's Appointment Held Unlawful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A ten-member bench of the
Supreme Court on Tuesday held in an unanimous decision the
appointment of Justice Sajjad Ali Shah as Chief Justice of
Pakistan as invalid.
</P>
<P>
The bench headed by Justice Saiduzzaman Siddiqui in its short
order said that the appointment of Sajjad as Chief Justice of the
Supreme Court is "invalid, unlawful and unconstitutional," and
asked the federal government to appoint Justice Ajmal Mian as the
Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
"He ceased to be the Chief Justice of Pakistan," Justice
Siddiqui read out the order in the jampacked Court Room Number two
in the Supreme Court building.
</P>
<P>
The bench said that all orders passed by Justice Sajjad after
November 26 were issued "without lawful authority" and hence are
invalid.
</P>
<P>
The two member bench of the Supreme Court at Quetta, capital of
Baluchistan province, had restrained Sajjad from acting as Chief
Justice of the country on November 26 because he was not the
senior most judge in the apex court when he was elevated to the
post three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had witnessed a worst-ever constitutional crisis
involving Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Chief Justice Sajjad
during the past four months.
</P>
<P>
The crisis culminated in the resignation of President Farooq
Leghari on December 2, who refused to sign a reference against
Sajjad as required by the government.
</P>
<P>
Following Leghari's stepping down, Sajjad has applied for a
two-and-half-month long leave till February 16 next year when his
retirement is due. Ajmal Mian, the second senior most judge of
the Supreme Court, was then sworn in as the Acting Chief Justice.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City's Workers Pitching in Housing Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1.02 million
workers and staff members, or 70 percent of the work force in this
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, have participated in
public accumulative fund for housing.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, these employees, most of whom are
working with the state- and collectively-owned businesses, had set
aside 1.7 billion yuan (205 billion US dollars) on the housing
fund.
</P>
<P>
The city implemented on a compulsory basis the public
accumulative fund for housing among the employees working with
state- and collectively-owned businesses in 1992. The fund is
aimed at pooling capital to build more apartment flats for the
workers who are without adequate housing.
</P>
<P>
Each institution and each employee working with that
institution are required to deposit seven percent of their
respective monthly salaries for the housing fund.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city has accelerated the pace for drafting the
relevant managerial measures for extending the housing fund to to
be implemented in the overseas-funded enterprises where 400,000
Chinese employees are working and private businesses and
individual industrial and commercial households, where 550,000
workers are employed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the municipal people's congress has also published a
regulation governing the implementation of the public accumulative
fund for housing.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the construction of three major
residential quarters in the city has proceeded smoothly thanks to
the aid of the fund. It will make it possible for the city's
20,000-strong households with a per-capita living space of less
than five sq m to move into newly-built apartment flats, which
will be sold at 1,800 yuan per sq m at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Beginning next year, the city will shift the focus of its
housing development to construction of comfortable-living housing
which will be sold at 3,000 yuan (360 US dollars) per sq m. It has
set forth a goal of increasing the city's per-capita living space
to 12 sq m by the end of this century, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Drafts Asset Valuation Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China is drafting a
comprehensive set of rules for asset valuation,
according to the Chinese Association of Asset Valuation (CAAV).
</P>
<P>
The rules will include basic, concrete and explanatory clauses
covering valuation concepts, pricing, business qualifications,
ethics and different stipulations for the valuation of enterprise
assets, real estate, intangible assets and resources, according to
the CAAV.
</P>
<P>
China's asset valuation industry has developed rapidly since
its establishment in the late 1980s. By the end of last year,
China had 3,343 asset valuation agencies with some 55,700
employees and a combined business volume of more than three
trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The CAAV issued trial rules on asset valuation in May, 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
