<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes GCC Call for Better Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran today welcomed a call of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) for better relations, saying
Tehran is ready to improve ties and cooperation with the Gulf
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Radio reported that spokesman of Iran's Foreign
Ministry Mahmoud Mohammadi was responding to a communique issued
at the end of the GCC summit in Kuwait Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that one of the priorities of Iran's foreign
policy is to expand friendly relations and cooperation with its
neighbors, the Gulf Arab states in particular, which would help
maintain peace, security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The GCC leaders on Monday expressed welcome to the recent
reconciliatory remarks of Iranian President Mohammad Khatami,
calling for better relations and cooperation with Iran in order to
establish mutual confidence and maintain regional security and
peace.
</P>
<P>
They also gave backing to any meetings between leaders of Iran
and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) to resolve their dispute over
the three islands of Abu Musa, the Greater and Lesser Tunbs in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The GCC announced UAE President Sheik Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan has accepted the proposal of his Iranian counterpart
Khatami that the leaders of the two countries meet to solve the
issue.
</P>
<P>
However, they reaffirmed support to the UAE's sovereignty over
the three islands and "all positions, measures and means to
restore them peacefully." The islands are now under the control of
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman reiterated the three islands belong to
Iran, saying that the UAE should hold bilateral talks with Iran to
remove the "misunderstandings" between them.
</P>
<P>
The islands are strategically located on the edge of the Strait
of Hormuz, the only gateway to the Gulf, through which much of the
world's oil passes.
</P>
<P>
Both Tehran and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the
islands despite their agreement to co-rule the islands in the Gulf
following the British withdrawal from the region in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Failing to reach a settlement after protracted talks, Abu Dhabi
announced to resort to the International Court of Justice in the
Hague, while Tehran insisted on solving the dispute through
bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi will pay an official
visit to the UAE after the summit of the GCC, which was founded in
1981 and groups the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Oman and
Bahrain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
