<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economy Stays Firm in Regional Turmoil (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's
services-dominated economy has maintained its vigor over a
full-blown "Asian flu" which threw many of Asian economies into
jitters, and an overall good performance is expected in the year
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, overshadowed by the financial turmoil in Southeast
Asia, the "last domino left standing" entered into an adjustment
period in the last quarter of this year, which will probably last
until the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
But a government-estimated 5.5 percent growth for 1997 is still
expected, as a 6.3 percent increase recorded for the first half of
the year offered some cushion.
</P>
<P>
Gross Domestic Product (GDP), underpinned by robust domestic
demand, increased by 6.1 percent and 6.4 percent in the first and
second quarters respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, growth slowed down to a preliminary five
percent, and is likely to ease further in the last quarter as the
regional turmoil, which has yet to settle down, is taking its
toll.
</P>
<P>
In spite of a sour adjustment which seems inevitable, Hong Kong
will be the first to bounce back among the affected Asian
economies thanks to its sound fundamentals and historical
resilience, Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa told world
economic leaders in Canada last month.
</P>
<P>
The confidence of the chief executive and his fellow city folk
was underpinned by the fact that Hong Kong has withstood the
severe test, with its status as an international hub for finance,
trade and shipping intact.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, the local financial
market was very active and the stock market, ranking the sixth
largest in the world in terms of market capitalization, was
particularly buoyant. The benchmark Hang Seng Index kept setting
new records and soared to over 16,000 points in early August.
</P>
<P>
In late October, international speculators, who had claimed a
victory in the currency and equity markets of Southeast Asia,
targeted Hong Kong. They mounted an intensive attack on the Hong
Kong dollar, reeling 1,438 points off the Hang Seng Index on
October 28, the largest single-day point retreat in the index's
history.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the dive with the 1987 crashdown, however, people
were quite relieved to find that Hong Kong's equity market had
been fledged. Shares changed hands in a smooth and orderly manner
with the help of advanced trading and settling mechanism, in
contrast to sheer chaos a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar has remained stable in the battle, with
the linked exchange rate successfully defended at the 7.8 level,
against the tumbling of other regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
During the troubled month of October, a continued double-digit
year-on-year growth was recorded with Hong Kong dollar deposits,
while Hong Kong's foreign reserves, the third largest in the
world, edged up 4.2 percent against a month earlier to stand at
91.8 billion U.S. dollars at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
But the Hong Kong economy paid a price for interest rate rises
made as part of the battle to fend off speculators. Along with the
plunge in the stock market, property market shrank by around 20
percent and retailing was also affected.
</P>
<P>
It was argued that a correction of property prices would
benefit Hong Kong's competitiveness as high rental costs have
always been cited by foreign investors as a most unfavorable
factor for doing business here.
</P>
<P>
Financial specialists believe that, given a sustainable
economic growth on China's inland area, there exists limitless
potential for Hong Kong's position as an international financial
center, well preserved after July 1 and tested by the regional
storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economy Stays Firm in Regional Turmoil (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The industry has been positive in predicting that the
mainland's restructuring of state-owned enterprises bodes well for
Hong Kong, which is a premier site for the enterprises to raise
funds.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Hong Kong's status as a trading center has
also been maintained as the year has witnessed modest export
growth. In 1995 and 1996, Hong Kong was placed seventh in world
trade by the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Government figures showed that the value of total exports in
the first 10 months of 1997 stood at 1,207 billion HK dollars (155
billion U.S. dollars), up 4 percent over the same period of last
year, while that of imports increased by 5.6 percent to 1,344
billion HK dollars (172 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland accounted for one-third of Hong Kong's
total trade.
</P>
<P>
In a trade outlook report for 1998, the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC) projected a five percent growth in value
terms for next year's merchandise exports, one percentage point
lower than the estimated five percent growth for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will not be spared from the negative regional
environment, but the impact should be limited, said the TDC,
because Southeast Asia and South Korea, which were hit hard by the
financial turmoil, account for a relatively small share of Hong
Kong's exports, while a differentiation in product composition
means their direct competition on third markets is relatively
limited.
</P>
<P>
And the total trade picture for Hong Kong would be better than
what statistics indicate, because an increasing number of Hong
Kong companies are involved in offshore trade. The TDC observed
that the growth of total export business managed by Hong Kong
companies should be around one to two percentage points higher
than the value increase captured by trade statistics.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's export of services increased by 5.3 percent in the
first half of this year, compared with an 8.6 percent increase for
the whole of 1996, and the growth is likely to decelerate further
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in services export was caused by a major downturn
in the tourism industry, but partially offset by healthy
performance in the freight transport sector.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters, tourism receipts decreased by 9.2
percent, a result of a 6.5 percent drop in the number of tourists
and a 3.4 percent contraction in per capita spending.
</P>
<P>
In spite of moderate export growth, Hong Kong's transport
services benefited from soaring transshipment business, generated
by strong growth of exports from Hong Kong-invested firms on the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months, Hong Kong's total container
throughput reached 9.4 million Twenty-foot Equivalent Units
(TEUs), up 9.2 percent from a year ago, with transshipment cargo
accounting for 21 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Air cargo throughput, at the overcrowded Kai Tak airport, has
grown at an even faster pace, up 15.5 percent in the first 10
months to reach 1.38 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The TDC expected services exports to pick up slightly next
year, fueled by a bottoming out of the tourism industry and a
steady growth in trade-supporting services.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rate remained low, standing at a little over 2
percent in the first nine months while underemployment for the
same period moved between 1 and 2 percent, demonstrating a
tightened labor market out of good economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The forecast for this year's consumer price inflation was
revised by the government from 6.5 percent down to 6 percent as
inflationary pressures continued to ease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Considers Laws to Counter Escapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- South African Justice
Ministerr Dullah Omar said that the government is considering
legislation to counter the number of criminals escaping from custody
while being transported from jails to courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with local television on Monday
night, Omar said "We are considering a proposal which will enable us
to hold court at prisons in certain specific instances."
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department is also considering hearing in prisons bail
applications in prison from prisoners already in custody, Omar said.
</P>
<P>
"It may mean the amendment of the Criminal Procedures Act in
certain respects and we are looking at that," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to prevent escapes from South African jails, the
Deaprtment of Correctional Services has issued directives for stricter
security measures to be implemented during festive season visits to
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Correctionsl Services spokesman for Gauteng Province Rudi
Potgieter said yesterday the measures were introduced specifically
to reduce prison escapes over this period.
</P>
<P>
So far this year 1,036 prisoners have escaped from prisons
countrywide. Last year, with a prison population of 118,731, there had
been 1,345 escapes.
</P>
<P>
There will be no more open days or sports days for the estimated
140,000 prisoners in South African jails, prison authorities said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there will be stricter searching of visitors when they
visit prisoners to prevent anything from being smuggled into them and
prersonnel dealing with prisoners will also be searched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
