<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economy Stays Firm in Regional Turmoil (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the economic prospects of 1998, the International Monetary
Fund predicted a modest 4.1 percent growth for Hong Kong in its
latest World Economic Outlook report, which revised down earlier
estimates of global and regional growth.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng and Standard Chartered, two major banks in Hong Kong,
had earlier projected a real GDP growth of around four percent.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered said that the slowdown will mainly be felt
in the first half and a recovery may begin in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank's chief economist for North Asia
Kwok-chuen Kwok, Hong Kong's competitiveness as a services center
is of prime importance as the services sector accounts for about
84 percent of Hong Kong's GDP. In this respect, Hong Kong's
proximity to the Chinese mainland where trade, business or
finance-related services are in great demand will help the city
maintain its niche as a regional business center.
</P>
<P>
It is highly notable that, even after the high volatility in
the market, the economic confidence of local people still remains
at a decent level. A survey conducted by the Hong Kong Economic
Times in mid-November showed that 69 percent of local investors
planned to enter the local stock market in the next half year and
expected a rebound of the Hang Seng Index within 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The bullish sentiment is shared by foreign investors. The 1997
American Chamber of Commerce confidence survey released early this
month showed that 96 percent of American firms have a favorable or
very favorable outlook about Hong Kong's business environment over
the next five years, with the great majority planning to expand
operation here or conduct business as usual.
</P>
<P>
From the perspective of the Heritage Foundation of the United
States, Hong Kong remains the world's freest economy for the
fourth year in a row. Its transition into a special
administrative region of China and the recent market fluctuations
triggered by the Southeast Asian financial crisis "have done
nothing to alter its status as the world's most open setting in
which to pursue economic activity."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
