<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugee Population in Zimbabwe Reaches 1,564 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is hosting 1,564
refugees from more than 20 countries with the largest group being
226 from Rwanda, the daily The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Neignboring Burundi, also engulfed in ethnic strife, ranked
the second with 138 refugees in the country, while Somalia, which
has not known peace for more than five years, is the third with
124 people taking refuge in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 284 are children, 130 of them girls who usually
face severe hardships under such conditions.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted acting director of the Social Welfare
Ministry Claudius Kasere as saying, "While the ministry provides
infrastructure and overall supervision or management of the
transit center, U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) meets
the cost of all necessary needs for food commodities, clothing,
educational and health expenses."
</P>
<P>
Other non-governmental organizations complement UNHCR efforts
by providing educational and training services, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Other countries which contribute to Zimbabwe's refugee
population are Angola, the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Tanzania, Ghana, Liberia, Sudan, Uganda, Sierra Leone, Kenya,
Togo and Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
Upon being granted refugee status, these people were taught to
become self reliant, said Kasere.
</P>
<P>
"If he is without marketable skills he is trained and given
start-up capital to undertake a self-reliant project in the
community. If he has skills that are in demand, he is assisted
to join formal employment to fend for himself and his family," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the acting director, the refugee population in
Zimbabwe is still increasing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
