<HEADLINE> Hainan Expands Agricultural Cooperation With Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan-funded enterprises have
emerged as a driving force in the agriculture sector in Hainan,
China's southernmost island province, especially in terms of
applications of advanced agronomics.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 Taiwan enterprises have invested 150 million US
dollars in developing agriculture in the province.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has long been plagued by low-level agriculture, a fact
which local people attribute the insufficient use of science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, only 28 percent of the agronomic research findings
were applied to production, with the hybrid seed coverage standing
at 70 percent, and the figure for hybrid animal husbandry and
aquatic products reaching only 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hainan Yaonong Co. has opened five comprehensive
experimental development bases in the province and has helped more
than 3,000 rural households plant seedless watermelons and other
fruit on 1,100 ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investors have introduced over 80 new varieties of farm
produce and by-products, with related products selling well on
the domestic market, as well as in Japan, the Republic of Korea,
Singapore, and Malaysia. Local farmers are in turn enjoying good
returns.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan enterprises have also held technical training courses
for farmers and grass roots officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
