<HEADLINE> Torrential Rains May Affect Tanzania's Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Cotton
Lint and Seed Board (TCLSB) has predicted reduced production of
cotton if current torrential rains continue.
</P>
<P>
Too much water brought by the rains have attracted pests and
fostered the growth of seedlings, posing threats to the crop
whose planting season is during November and December, said TCLSB
General Manager Ally Ngongolo here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But Ngongolo did not disclose the amount of loss the board is
likely to incur if the crop fails, The Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
So far 24,000 tons of cotton seeds had been distributed to be
planted in 400,000 hectares of farmland in Mwanza, Shinyanga, Mara,
Kagera, Tabora, Singida and Mbeya regions.
</P>
<P>
On average, annual sales of the crop stood at 100 million US
dollars, Ngongolo said, adding that some 65 million US dollars
had been acquired from sales by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
The above-average seasonal rains caused by El Nino weather
phenomenon could also jeopardize prospects for coffee production,
said Tanzania Coffee Board managing director Leslie Omari last
week.
</P>
<P>
In the northern Kilimanjaro region, a major coffee growing
area, if rains continue to pour down, the flowers will abort and
form leaves. Worse is that some farmers have reported cases of
coffee berry disease (CBD) and coffee leaf rust, as a result of
excessive moisture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
