<HEADLINE> China's Personal Income Tax Revenues Hits 25 Billion Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- China expects to collect
more than 25 billion yuan (three billion US dollars) in personal
income taxes this year, according to official estimates.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the State Administration of Taxation
show that China's individual income tax revenues surged 36 percent
for the first 11 months of the year to 23.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's personal income tax revenues for last year stood at 19.3
billion yuan, up 47 percent on 1995.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, 10 provincial administrative areas had
overfulfilled their budgeted 1997 figure for personal income
taxes, with tax revenues for six areas surging by more than 50
percent during the January-November period.
</P>
<P>
An in-depth analysis indicates that south China's Guangdong
Province led all other provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions with personal income tax revenues of 3.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai ranked second with 2.9 billion yuan in personal income
taxes and Beijing, the Chinese capital, ranked third with 2.6
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Fujian and Shandong each had personal
income tax revenues of more than one billion yuan for the first 11
months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
