<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Declassifies Documents, Films of Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Energy Department
Monday released previously classified documents and films about the
nation's atomic blasts testing peaceful use of nuclear explosives
from 1961 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
Over all, the United States detonated 35 nuclear explosions in
27 peaceful tests. The tests were designed to use nuclear
explosives for construction of harbors, tunnels and canals as well
as for drilling and mining.
</P>
<P>
The first test was on December 10, 1961, at Carlsbad, New
Mexico, and the last on May 17, 1973, at Rifle, Colorado. Others
were at Farmington, New Mexico, and Grand Valley, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
The government for the first time released specific yields for
11 of the 27 test blasts for peaceful purposes, all but four at
the Nevada Test Site.
</P>
<P>
Most of the tests were contained under ground, ranging from
less than one kiloton to slightly more than 11 kilotons.
</P>
<P>
But one at the Nevada Test Site on July 6, 1962, was six times
the size of the bomb dropped at Hiroshima, displaced 12 million
tons of earth and released the seismic energy equivalent of an
earthquake with a magnitude of 4.75.
</P>
<P>
The department said that nuclear explosives for peaceful
purposes were never used by the United States though technically
successful.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, documents have been assumed to be born
classified. Starting today, that assumption is eliminated. Only
materials with a compelling national security interest will be
classified," said Energy Secretary Federico Pena, who previewed
the films with reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Research Institute Issues Alert Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Agricultural
Research Institute (KARI) has issued an alert over an outbreak of
a disease hitting the flower industry in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted KARI's senior entomologist G.N.
Kibata as saying that more than 10 flower farms
had reported heavy losses as a result of the bacterial
crown gall disease.
</P>
<P>
He told a flower growers' meeting held at the KARI
headquarters that "the most recent problem in the 1990s has been
crown gall introduced with rose seedlings and is already taking
a heavy toll on rose production."
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, J.C. Kedera, Managing Director of the
newly established Kenya Plant Health Inspectorate Services, said
that the disease could been traced back to the import of diseased
planting materials.
</P>
<P>
Virtually all consignments of rose seedlings arriving in the
country in the past two months have been found to be contaminated
with diseases or pests, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Plant Health Inspectorate has intercepted and
burnt at least 5,000 plants at the point of entry, excluding an
entire consignment seized and destroyed last week, according to
Kedera.
</P>
<P>
Horticulture is Kenya's fourth largest foreign exchange earner
and expected to overtake tea and coffee to become the second
largest foreign exchange earner in next two years.
</P>
<P>
Cut flowers have surpassed other horticultural products over
the past two years, earning the country 4.37 billion Kenyan
Shillings (about 70 million U.S. Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
