<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loan for Private Bangladeshi Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has approved a loan of 40 million U.S. dollars for setting up a
private joint-venture cement plant in Bangladesh, the local press
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank has agreed to provide 40 million dollars
in loans and 10 million dollars as equity investment for the
Lafarge Surma Cement Ltd, a project between Lafarge Group of
France and the Islam Group of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, which will become the largest and the most
modern cement plant in the country, will cost and estimated amount
of 225 million dollars, of which 90 million dollars will come as
equity and the rest as loans.
</P>
<P>
With an annual production capacity of 1.2 million tons of
cement, the plant will be set up at Chhatak in Sunamganj district,
northeast Bangladesh, and is scheduled to go into commercial
production in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
The plant is the fourth private project in Bangladesh so far to
have received direct assistance from the ADB.  
</P>
