<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Tighten Waste Disposal Norms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
constituted an experts panel to examine and suggest measures for
effective implementation of the existing toxic waste management
laws, said a senior official in the Environment and Forests
Ministry here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This complies with a Supreme Court directive on the issue,
which reflects the realization that further executive and
legislative measures are needed to protect the ecology from the
industrial toxic waste discharge.
</P>
<P>
The panel will examine the effectiveness of the present waste
management laws and suggest new legislative measures to make the
laws effective.
</P>
<P>
A major task before the panel is to identify new hazardous
wastes that need an immediate ban. These would be in addition to
those already banned under the Hazardous Waste (Management and
Handling) Rules of 1989 and the direction of the Basel Convention
on hazardous wastes, to which India is a signatory.
</P>
<P>
The panel has been particularly directed to study the import of
hazardous substances and suggested how their import could be
altogether stopped, or if such an import is unavoidable, then the
measures required to reduce their harmful effect.
</P>
<P>
The panel will make suggestions to promote production methods
which give out ecologically friendly products after eliminating or
reducing to the acceptable levels their toxic contents. It will
also make recommendations on the safe disposal of such wastes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
