<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Sugarcane Planters Demand Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai sugarcane planters are
demanding higher sugarcane prices to compensate for their higher
production costs, the newspaper The Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sugarcane production costs have risen significantly since the
baht was floated and the value-added tax increased earlier this
year, said Suphan Duangchampa, president of the Association of
Northeastern Sugarcane Planters.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have to pay higher interest rates on advances from
millers and high transport fees while fertilizer and labor costs
have also gone up.
</P>
<P>
Retail sugar prices in the country have been frozen for 17
years. About two months ago, the prices rose "unofficially" from
the controlled prices of 12-13 baht per kilogram to 15-16 baht.
But the planters did not benefit from the increases, Suphan said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
