<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Imports Fewer Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's car imports
 slumped by almost 20 percent in the year ending November,
Statistics New Zealand said in a press release received Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figures contained in the release showed a 4.7-percent drop
in imports from Asia, largely because of lower level of car
imports from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Over the past months, second-hand Japanese-made cars lost favor
among many New Zealanders following allegations that their
odometers had been tampered with.
</P>
<P>
Imports from other parts of Asia, including Malaysia, Singapore
and Hong Kong, also fell.
</P>
<P>
However, imports from China rose by 23.3 percent on the annual
basis, the statistical office said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Current Account Deficit Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's current
account deficit worsened in the year ending September, rising to
6.4 percent of the gross domestic product from 6.2 percent a year
ago, according to figures released by Statistics New Zealand
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the deficit is not as bad as forecast by some
economists, it is still the worst since December 1986.
</P>
<P>
Bancorp economist Stuart Marshall was quoted by a press report
as saying the lower than expected figures were a relief for
everyone, but it also meant that New Zealand did not look as
attractive to overseas investors as it did one year ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the deficit had been worse, the New Zealand
dollar would have fallen sharply.
</P>
<P>
The current account measures the flow of money for goods and
services between New Zealand and its trading partners.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand's figures show that the current account
data improved in the third quarter this year, standing at 2.22
billion NZ dollars (1.27 billion U.S. dollars) compared with 2.11
billion dollars (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) in the previous
quarter.
</P>
<P>
But on an annual basis, the deficit rose as a percentage of
GDP, it pointed out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
