<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US-China Relationship Stablized, Roth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official said
here on Monday that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's recent visit
to the United States has helped stablize the Sino-U.S. relationship.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary of State for East Asian and Pacific affairs
Stanley O. Roth told a press conference that positive changes have
taken place in 1997 and the government mobilized "considerable
bipartisan support in the Congress" for its China policy.
</P>
<P>
"If you go back to last January, you'll remember there were
enormous predictions about how much difficulty MFN was going to be
in; at this time, the Congress might really reject it; that there
was a lot of concern about Hong Kong reversion on top of all the
traditional issues with China policy that had figured in the
debate in previous years, and a sense that the relationship could
be in for a rocky period," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
He said the administration managed the MFN issue rather well
with MFN passed by over 80 votes, a rather large margin.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang made a tour of seven U.S. cities in eight
days, a milestone in the bilateral ties between the two countries.
One of the most important accomplishments is the agreement to
establish constructive strategic partnership for the next century.
</P>
<P>
Roth, who mostly was involved in the whole process, believed
that the state visit was a "major step forward in terms of
stabilizing the relationship" in spite of some still existing
problems
</P>
<P>
"I believe it set a different context for how we deal with
issues in terms of working towards a constructive strategic
partnership."
</P>
<P>
"I think there are many areas where we and the Chinese are
talking much more productively about substantive issues, whether
it's the Korean peninsula, South Asia, the Persian Gulf,
environmental issues or some of our bilateral issues," said Roth,
who accompanied Secretary of State Madeleine Albright during her
three visits this year to Asia and Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official was reviewing Washington's policy toward Asia
and the Pacific as a whole in the passing year. He claimed that the
better U.S.-China relationship is one of the most positive
changes in the region.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the development of bilateral ties will no
longer be tied to "the ups and downs in the political roller
coaster" as both sides agreed to progress wherever possible and
narrow or at least manage their differences.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Jiang and Bill Clinton agreed at their summit
meeting that high-level talks be held on regular basis. Clinton is
expected to return a state visit to China next spring, another
step to enhance the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Roth reiterated the U.S. One-China policy, saying there is no
effort to revise it.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the U.S. would like to play an important role
in helping solve the financial crisis in Asia, but he stressed
that the International Monetary Fund must take the lead.
</P>
<P>
On the region as a whole, Roth said that Asia and Pacific will
continue to be given high priority in the U.S. foreign policy, and
both the region and Europe are equally important to Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
