<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Air Force Seeks to Delay Payment for Purchases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Air Force is seeking
to extend payment periods for the procurement deals it has made
earlier as Thailand is suffering an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force has sought to postpone payment for seven
purchases to be made in the 1998 fiscal year, local newspapers
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They include the purchase of a batch of U.S. F-18 jet fighters,
four search and rescue helicopters, five medium-sized transport
planes and some radar systems.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Air Force has already managed, after talks with U.S.
suppliers, to extend the payment period for the purchase of the
jet fighters for three years with the last installment to be paid
in 2003, instead of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it hoped that the United States could help find a
third country to take over the jet fighters although it might face
a fine for breaching the contract, the newspapers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Overseas Market to Be Set Up in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A market selling Chinese-made
commodities will be opened next March in St. Paul of Brazil and the
preparatory work is under full swing.
</P>
<P>
According to officials in the Zhejiang Provincial government,
the market, China's first of its kind, will cover an area of 3,000
square meters and be located in a business building on the
25th Avenue, a commercial center in South America.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the market was initiated by the
governments of east China's Zhejiang Province and Wenzhou
city. And up to now, three million U.S. dollars has been spent on
the market by the China Market Co. Ltd., which is in charge of its
construction and management.
</P>
<P>
The marketplace aims at helping local enterprises find foreign
business opportunities, and promote local commodities in
international markets, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the first 50 businesses that will have their
presence at the market are based in Wenzhou, and produce
low-voltage electrical appliances, auto parts, arts and crafts,
shoes, garments and lamps, among others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
