<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Chamber Urges Delinking Economy From Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 23 (Xinhua)-- The Associated Chamber of
Commerce and Industry of India (ASSOCHAM) has appealed to all
political parties in India to delink economic policies from
politics so that economic development does not suffer on account
of political instability.
</P>
<P>
In an economic agenda prepared by ASSOCHAM for adoption by
political parties, which was released here on Monday, ASSOCHAM
President L. Lakshman noted that implementation of economic
reforms has slowed down because of political postures.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that political parties of all hues set for
themselves a common agenda to actualize the country's potential to
emerge as a global economic power," he said.
</P>
<P>
The objective of releasing such an agenda paper is to secure a
broad national consensus on economic policies so that economic
development does not suffer on account of political instability,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The next government should target gross domestic product growth
averaging about 8 percent over the next five years while industry,
agriculture and service should grow by 11 percent, 4 percent and
10 percent respectively by the year 2003, Lakshman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the gross domestic savings ratio should reach 30
percent, fiscal deficit be reduced to 2.5 percent and aggregate
subsidies cut down to 5 percent of the GDP, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
