<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Largest Automaker to Increase Sales in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's largest
automaker, Daewoo Motor Corporation, said Monday that it plans to
open 40 to 50 stores in the United States in 1998 to make their
low-cost small cars available to U.S. customers.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo's subsidiary in Ohio said the stores will be Daewoo
owned factory-direct stores where customers can buy cars, parts
and get service, quite different from standard U.S. franchise
dealerships which just sell cars.
</P>
<P>
Three models of Daewoo -- the midsize Leganza, compact Nubira
and subcompact Lanos -- are expected to be sold to U.S. customers,
with Lanos at prices between 9,000 to 12,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Lanos model is seen as strong competitor to its
counterparts manufactured by General Motors, Ford Motor and
Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
They fear that South Korean and Japanese automakers will pour
exports into the U.S. market next year in response to economic
crisis at home and falling value of the Japanese yen and South
Korean won.
</P>
<P>
That will intensify price war that already has eaten into
sales by the Big Three, and has forced them to boost discounts to
more than 2,000 dollars per vehicle in the United States,
according to CNW marketing, a research firm in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo, with a share of 2.5 percent of international market, is
expected to make 1.39 million cars and trucks in 1997, with a
total revenue of 16.7 billion dollars including 11.7 billion at
home and five billion overseas.
</P>
<P>
The company is aiming at raising its production to 2.5 million
cars and trucks by the year 2000 and increasing its total revenue
to 40 billion dollars in three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
