<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Ends Bosnia Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, December 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
left Bosnia Monday evening after a one-day visit to Sarajevo and
Tuzla where U.S. troops are based.
</P>
<P>
On a holiday mission to thank American troops and encourage
Bosnia's fragile peace, Clinton lectured the nation's three
presidents on Monday to set aside differences and rebuild their
government.
</P>
<P>
"You owe it to your country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told the Bosnian leaders in a private meeting in Sarajevo
that U.S. peacekeeping help is not infinite and the world
"rightfully expects that you do your part."
</P>
<P>
"The future is up to you, not to the Americans, not to the
Europeans, not to anyone else," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton pledged that Americans would do their best to enforce
the 1995 Dayton peace accords, which ended the three and a half
year ethnic war in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton last week indefinitely extended the mandate of some
8,500 U.S. troops serving with the NATO-led peacekeeping force in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also held a meeting with Bosnian Serb President
Biljana Plavsic, who asked Clinton for patience. "Slowly, one can
expect results, but certain things cannot be implemented quickly,"
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
