<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Analysts Not Surprised by Moody's Downgrading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Thai finance analysts are not
surprised when Moody's Investors Service further downgraded
Thailand's foreign currency credit for bonds and notes to junk
status, according to the newspaper The Nation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The international rating agency on Monday lowered Thailand's
foreign-currency bonds and notes rating to Ba1 from Baa3,
affecting all 11 major Thai commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The news of the downgrading only moderately affected the stock
exchange and money market as the downgrade had already been
discounted by the markets as expected.
</P>
<P>
A dealer of Bangkok Bank, which was also affected, said, "It
did not give us a big shock and the market reacted moderately to
the news. We have begun to get used to downgrades."
</P>
<P>
The baht dropped slightly on the news, with Bangkok Bank
quoting a high of 47.2, a low of 46.4, and a close of 47.2 to the
U.S. dollar. The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index finished
8.3 points, or 2.15 percent, lower to close at 376.95 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers and analysts admit that amidst the persistent economic
slump, the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
However, they say the downgrade will affect outstanding and
future debt instruments issued by Thai corporations and state
agencies and will significantly increase the cost of new
borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Reducing Thai foreign currency bonds and notes to junk status
may also limit the chances of local banks and finance companies to
raise funds internationally, they noted. For instance, because of
the higher risks, U.S. financial institutions are not permitted to
invest in junk bonds.
</P>
<P>
This will mean that foreign capital is not likely to flow back
into the country as earlier expected.
</P>
<P>
Moody's downgrading of Thailand's foreign currency credit
reflects foreign investors' continued concern over the country's
credit and financial fundamentals, the analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
