<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. Hold Talks on Anti-Drug Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The preparation work for
setting up a Multilateral Anti-Drug Center (MADC) in Panama took a
new step as negotiators from Panama and the United States settled
on some controversial issues in their weekend talks, Panamanian
congressman Aleman Boyd said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the latest round of talks over the weekend in Panama
City, Panamanian negotiator Jorge Eduardo Ritter and his
U.S. counterpart Thomas McNamara settled on controversial issues
like the jurisdiction of the center and its characteristics and
functions.
</P>
<P>
The United States suggested that the MADC enjoy
extraterritoriality and that U.S. officials be granted diplomatic
ranks, the congressman said.
</P>
<P>
Boyd said that negotiators also agreed on the U.S. military
presence at the MADC, saying that military personnel will be
working in the center in very specific tasks.
</P>
<P>
"Sophisticated equipment at the MADC, such as planes and
radars, will be managed by U.S. military technicians," he added.
</P>
<P>
As for other Latin American countries, the legislator said that
Brazil, Mexico and Colombia have shown intention in taking part.
</P>
<P>
He said that the financing of the multilateral body will be
shared proportionally by member nations.
</P>
<P>
The center is part of efforts to curb drug trafficking in the
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian press reports said that the operation of the MADC
will last 12 years, with a five-year period of possible extension.
</P>
<P>
The next round of talks on the MADC between Ritter and McNamara
will take place in Miami, the United States, where accords on
remaining issues are expected to be reached.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian President Ernesto Perez Balladares has announced his
decision to culminate negotiations before the year ends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
