<HEADLINE> Fiat to Set Up Joint Venture With Russian Automaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian auto giant Fiat and
Russia's second-biggest carmaker Gaz signed an 850-million-dollar
deal on Monday to set up a joint venture in Russia to make Fiat
cars.
</P>
<P>
The new venture, to be set up on the basis of the Gaz plant at
Nizhni Novgorod, 430 kilometers east of Moscow, is expected to
have an annual production capacity of 150,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
Among the investment, the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development will grant a loan of 240 million U.S. dollars to the
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the plant's 4,000-strong labor force will
initially assemble parts made in Italy. Later on parts will be
made in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Gaz, employing 100,000 people, produced 220,000 cars last year.
</P>
<P>
The deal was agreed on September 29, 1997, 31 years after Fiat
opened its car factory at Togliattigrad, a Russian auto city built
in the 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
