<HEADLINE> Another Group Suspected of Role in Sri Lanka Blasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A series of recent bomb
attacks on electricity transformers in Sri Lanka have alerted
police intelligence to probe whether another organized violent
group other than the LTTE was involved in these destructive
activities.
</P>
<P>
Police in Colombo said Tuesday they are carrying out
investigations to track down those responsible and government
analysts have been also called in to offer help.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been rocked by a spate of blasts targeted at
electricity transformers recently.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, a main transformer of the Jayanthipura Power
Substation was bombed, cutting off power supply to Polonnaruwa
Town in North Central Province.
</P>
<P>
In Bandarawela, Uva Province, two heavy-duty transformers were
damaged last Thursday when two explosive devices went off
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Similar incidents have also been reported in Badulla, capital
of Uva Province in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Police had previously blamed the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) for the attacks. But now they are also looking into
the possibility that the blasts were carried out by an unknown
violent group.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police investigations into the explosion of fuel
tanks at a private gas station in Hatton, Central Province, early
this month have revealed that it was the work of a local gang and
not the LTTE.  
</P>
</TEXT>
