<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Tourism in Costa Rica will surge 4 percent this
year according to the Costa Rican Institute of Tourism (CRIT).
</P>
<P>
The Central American country hosted last November more than
49,000 foreign visitors, an increase of 5.38 percent against
November 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the country was visited by 501,000 foreign tourists,
3.98 percent less than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Wheat growers in Argentina have lost some 150
million dollars due to scarce rains -- might be caused by the El
Nino phenomenon -- the authorities reported.
</P>
<P>
Losses are caused by delayed precipitations in the
wheat-producing region, covering the provinces of Buenos Aires,
Cordoba, La Pampa and Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Exports of Brazilian poultry reached 900 million
dollars this year, 8 percent less than that of last year.
</P>
<P>
The original total sales' target for the year was one billion
dollars, but the economic crisis in Asia contracted those
countries' markets, experts said.
</P>
<P>
They predicted that poultry exports will not earn in the first
half of 1998 the total value of 405.5 million dollars that was
reached in the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- Tourism in Colombia grew 4.2 percent this
year, the National Council of Economic and Social Policy reported.
</P>
<P>
The surge includes the services in hotels and restaurants but
excludes travel agencies and airlines.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Tax collection deficit in Uruguay amounted to 346
million dollars over the first eight months, equivalent to 1.3
percent of the Gross National Product. 
</P>
