<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Expected to Slow Down in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian economy is
estimated to grow at a rate of less than 3 percent in 1998 due to
unstable regional economic growth following the currency turmoil
in Southeast Asia and Far East this year, an economist said.
</P>
<P>
The estimated growth is realistic enough because the worst
impact of the crisis will be felt in 1998, Mari Elka Pangestu,
executive director of the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, said at a seminar on economy here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia recorded an economic growth rate of 7.9 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The country is still influenced by uncertainties affecting
regional growth and by the monetary turmoil in countries such as
South Korea and Japan, Antara News Agency Tuesday quoted Pangestu
as saying.
</P>
<P>
If the uncertainties were also experienced by China and Japan,
the impact would eventually spread to the United States and the
aftermath of the uncertainties would be felt all over the world,
she said.
</P>
<P>
She also predicted that inflation in the country this year
would exceed 10 percent, much higher than last year's 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country may see even higher inflation next year, she said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Anggito Abimanyu, an economic observer at Gajah Mada
University, said Indonesia's economic growth would be at the level
of 2-3 percent.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the decline to a decrease in consumption,
investment and the state budget.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Indonesian currency, the rupiah, has dropped
by more than 100 percent against the U.S. dollar since early July
this year following the monetary crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
