<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Paying Attention to White Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Yao Tong, owner of a food shop
in the southern part of Beijing, saw a plastic bag waving in the
wind on the top of a tree in front of his shop, and found a pole
to pick it down, then threw it into a trash can.
</P>
<P>
Yao said, "Many TV programs are encouraging people to control
white pollution and lots of environmental protection officials and
policemen are cleaning the streets these days."
</P>
<P>
After the leaves falling down in the crisp winter, many plastic
bags can be found hanging on the trees along Beijing's main
streets. This year the municipal government decided to take
measures to control the white pollution including the rampant
quick food boxes thrown by people carelessly.
</P>
<P>
One of the city's aims is to reclaim 30 percent of the waste
boxes especially in the tourist areas and the commercial streets,
said an official.
</P>
<P>
The shops and markets are prohibited from offering the plastic
bags that can be used for only once, he added.
</P>
<P>
The city's media have strengthen their propagation efforts
among the residents to reclaim the plastic packages.
</P>
<P>
An official from Beijing Municipal Environment and Health
Administration said that the residents should not throw away the
plastic bags carelessly, which may cause difficulties for street
cleaners.
</P>
<P>
So far, most of the cleaning work is done by the sanitation
workers. Only a few ordinary citizens do the cleaning work on
their own accord like Yao Tong.
</P>
<P>
However, "to Educate and mobilize the masses" has been one of
the nation's effective ways in doing everything well, including
the fight against white pollution, said the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern River Shipping Management System Operational in Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A vessel traffic system (VTS)
was put into use recently on a section of the lower Yangtze River,
which is dubbed the "golden waterway of China".
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the operation of the facility marks a major
step in modernizing China's inland waterway traffic management.
</P>
<P>
The VTS, with a cost of 100 million yuan (12 million US
dollars), has been built in a 364-kilometer waterway from Nanjing,
capital of Jiangsu Province, to Nantong City through Zhenjiang and
Zhangjiagang cities. It is believed to be the longest of its
kind in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Equipped with the systems of radar information, micro-wave
transmission, radar data processing display, automatic
meteorological services, and vessel information, the facility can
provide vessel supervision, traffic coordination, salvage,
pollution prevention, and information services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
