<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Unveils Aid Package to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Italy will provide 20 billion
lire (11.4 million U.S. dollars) in aid to Albania to help further
stablize the country which suffered widespread unrest triggered by
collapse of pyramid investment schemes earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The package, aimed at protecting women and children, creating
jobs and encouraging Albanians to stay in their own country, was
put forth by Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano and Social
Affairs Minister Livia Turoo.
</P>
<P>
Of the aid money, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
will get 3.4 billion lire (2 million dollars), the International
Social Service will get 1.5 billion (870,000 dollars) for programs
to help Albanian youths in Italy return home, and various
non-governmental organizations and local agencies will receive
14.5 billion (8.4 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The package contains measures that seek to create jobs for
women, thus protecting them from the prostitution rings, Turoo
said.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,500 children in poor families will also benefit from the
package, which will provide aid for their education and create
family centers for those minors most at risk, he added.
</P>
<P>
Programs to help alcoholics and drug addicts will also be
started.
</P>
<P>
A team of Italian and Albanian experts will monitor the aid
efforts and evaluate their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
Italy led the international effort to restore order in the
troubled Balkan country. More than 17,000 Albanians fled to Italy
during and in the wake of the unrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Shanghai, A Paradise for Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has become a place
where foreigners think they can make huge profits and they have
actually done so.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Shanghai Committee for Foreign Investment
show that during the first 11 months of this year foreign-funded
firms in Shanghai poured in 4.89 billion US dollars of additional
investment, accounting for 17 percent of the total foreign capital
flowing into the city.
</P>
<P>
"We have drawn benefit from investing in China, and Shanghai is
our first stop in China," said a senior executive of the
Bristol-Myers Squibb of the US.
</P>
<P>
Several years ago the company brought only five million US
dollars to began its adventure in Shanghai, a traditional paradise
for foreign investors since early this century.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign investors eyed the Squibb as a stone to test the
water on the Chinese market. To date, the successful company has
increased its investment by more than 20 million US dollars in
Shanghai alone, and its investment in the whole China has
ballooned to 100 million.
</P>
<P>
More companies have been following the road the Squibb
pioneered to increase investment. From January to September this
year, more than 10 Japanese companies have doubled their
investment in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Rhone-Poulence group from France has recently built a
technology park in Shanghai, involving a total of 24 million US
dollars. "This is just a beginning for us. We will continue to
expand our business in China," said Jean-Marc Bruel, deputy
president of the transnational corporation.
</P>
<P>
Economists attribute the fever to the good economic and
political situation in Shanghai, and in China as a whole, which
has made foreign economic giants to renew their China strategies.
</P>
<P>
Investment at a large scale and in a systematic way has become
the latest trend, economists say, with more capital flowing to
sectors of finance, insurance and trade.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows that some investors from the US, Japan and the
European Community thought that Shanghai is a moderately developed
society and its comprehensive conditions are good for business
operation.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai municipal government's efforts in improving
investment environment, in addition to the central government's
policy of developing the Yangtze River valley with Shanghai at the
leading position, have also drawn foreigners' attention,
economists say.
</P>
<P>
They add that foreign investors are confident in Shanghai
because it has a 100-year-old tradition of developing modern
commerce and trade, and it is now the largest industrial city and
the centers of finance, commerce and shipping in China.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 80 percent of foreign-funded firms in Shanghai have
reported good results.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai municipal government has vowed to guarantee a
normalized market for foreign businessmen, and it says that the
added investment by those already operational in Shanghai will
account for one-fourth of the newly attracted foreign capital
around the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
