<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are some of
the important economic news in Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico was the second largest market for United
States` exports during 1997, replacing Japan. Mexico also was the
second largest commercial partner of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government said that the country bought goods from
the United States worth 58.4 billion dollars, compared to 54.8
billion dollars from Japan. Canada ranks first as purchaser of
U.S. goods.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The major Argentine steel company, Techint,
heads the conglomerate that won the public auction of the
Venezuela`s state-run steel company Sidor.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerate that now owns Sidor comprises Techint, with a
40-percent share; Venezuela`s Sivensa, 20 percent; Mexico`s
Hylsamex, 30 percent and Brazil`s Usiminas, 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean trade is expected to increase 5.5 percent
this year than that of 1996, the National Chamber of Commerce
(NCC) reported.
</P>
<P>
Trade increased 3.1 percent over the first half year and is
expected to rise 7.4 percent over the second half. The growth is
due mainly to the increase of trade in garment, footwear and
retail businesses.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The sales of imported vehicles in Brazil were
37 percent higher over the first 11 months than a year earlier,
while the home-made vehicles increased just by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that in 1998, imported vehicles will take
a bigger share in the Brazilian market.
</P>
<P>
Audi expects to sell 7,000 units in 1998, a 50-percent rise
against this year, and Volvo looks forward to reaching 1,100
vehicles, a growth of 30 percent with respect to its 1997 sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
