<HEADLINE> 110,000 Elders in East China City Attend University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Every day, Wei Shanxun, 70,
goes to a local university for a computer course for the elderly
in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
"I bought a computer recently, and I have learned how to use it
for writing and family management," he said, adding 32 seniors
from all walks of life are attending the course.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Jingzhen, a retired middle school teacher, said that her
goal to learn to use computers is to follow the social and
economic development and keep in closer touch with the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
With a senior population of 3.31 million, the province has made
great efforts to develop education for old people in recent years.
At present, Fujian has established 1,733 universities or
schools for the elderly with a combined enrolment of 110,000
people.
</P>
<P>
Li Qingzao, deputy president of the Fujian Provincial
Association of Education for the Elderly, said that the province
will carry out diversified educational projects to provide more
chances for local seniors to receive education.
</P>
<P>
The province is to attract four to eight percent of urban
elders, and one to two percent of rural elders to attend such
schools by 2000, Li said .  
</P>
</TEXT>
