<HEADLINE> Western Nations Boost Aid to Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A number of western countries are
planning to boost their technical aid to Ukraine next year, the
Ukrainian National Agency for Reconstruction and Development
announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sweden plans to build up assistance levels in 1998 to 20
million Swedish kronor (2.56 million U.S. dollars) from 14 million
kronor (1.79 million U.S. dollars). They wish to implement five
projects concerned with democracy building, environmental
protection, energy conservation and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland is prepared to grant Ukraine at least seven million
Swiss francs (4.7 million U.S. dollars) to help fund neonatal
health care projects which will be introduced in several regions
of Ukraine. Although financial implementation of the project will
begin next year, the final cost has not been set.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland will provide an additional 14 million Swiss francs
(9.4 million U.S. dollars) over five years for hydroelectric power
projects.
</P>
<P>
The United States will maintain its current level of aid to
Ukraine at 225 million dollars. Of this, 25 million dollars will
go to the International Nuclear Safety Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
