<HEADLINE> Poland, China Sign Trade Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 21 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to reduce Poland's
trade deficit with China, the two countries signed three
agreements Sunday to increase China's imports from Poland.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, China will buy 60 million U.S. dollars
worth of electrolytic copper from Poland, and expand its imports of
cars and parts, and chemical industry equipment and techniques.
</P>
<P>
The agreements came just one month after Polish President
Aleksander Kwasniewski's visit to China during which he pledged to
reinforce economic and trade cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume between Poland and China once reached
one billion U.S. dollars in the mid-1980s, but plunged to only
144 million U.S. dollars in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two has improved rapidly in recent years,
with a considerable favorable balance on China's side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
