<HEADLINE> East China City Striving to Eradicate Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Hefei, capital of east China's
Anhui Province, has carried out polio vaccination programs to
bring the incidence of the common infant disease further down.
</P>
<P>
No cases of polio have been reported in the city over the past
six years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show more than 95 percent of the children in the
city's urban areas and 90 percent in its rural areas have been
inoculated against polio from 1991 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Every year, some 50,000 newly-born babies are included in the
programs.
</P>
<P>
Eight rounds of polio vaccinations have been carried out
on the children aged four or below in the city.
</P>
<P>
The city government has equipped local clinics and epidemic
prevention centers in urban and rural areas with facilities for
the storage of the vaccines.
</P>
<P>
The city is resolved to wipe out the "wild polio virus" and
polio infection by the turn of the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Money Creates Insane Results (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The season turned an upside down in late October when Chinese
famous coach Ma Junren let his younger generation of "Ma's family
army" smash all the year-best marks from the women's 800m to
marathon at the Chinese National Games in Shanghai, a repeat
miracle Ma's troop displayed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Jiang Bo, 1995 world number one, ran 14
minutes and 28.09 seconds to set a new 5,000m world record.
</P>
<P>
Another incredible achievement came when Li Xuemei, a second
round qualifier in the 100m in Athens, hit the tape in 10.79
seconds, a time much faster than the world champion's clocking.
</P>
<P>
The sudden burst of excellence was a sharp contrast to China's
medal-free finish at the world championships, and this elicited
whispers again that the Chinese were taking drugs.
</P>
<P>
However, the doping suspicion found no ground as all Ma's
soldiers and Li passed IAAF drug tests.
</P>
<P>
The year also saw a grotesque 150-meter race between Canadian
Bonovan Bailey and American Michael Johnson to prove who was the
world fastest human.
</P>
<P>
But sadly, it was a production in which the distinction
between good and evil were somewhat blurred.
</P>
<P>
The race, offering a record one million U.S. dollars for the
winner, turned out a great fuss, and disappointed the world TV
viewers and IAAF as well.
</P>
<P>
Bailey led the way off the curve with a visible lead, but
Johnson, the Athlete of the World last year, grabbed his left
thigh painfully in the wake, and limped to a stop.
</P>
<P>
"I felt the cramp grab, then it let go. I kept going, but I
felt it again and it was much worse," claimed Johnson.
</P>
<P>
"He didn't pull up, he's a chicken. I think what we should do
is run this race over so I can kick his ass one more time,"
retorted Bailey.
</P>
<P>
The race aimed to promote track and field profile, but created
madness instead.
</P>
<P>
Carl Lewis of the United States, owner of nine Olympic golds,
bid farewell to the track and field after a glorious career at
age of 37.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Bubka, who has broken the world record for 35 times in
the men's pole vault, underlined his superiority by landing the
world title in a record six times at the Athens Worlds, which
marked a time of transition for the sport.
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones of the United States, a Lewis style
sprinter-jumper and an outstanding leader of young rising stars,
won the world women's 100m title and the crown of the Woman
Athlete of the Year.
</P>
<P>
Just before the world championships, the biennial IAAF
Congress voted to amend doping bans. Despite the relative
lopsided vote, some Congress members believed that the new policy
would make it cheaper to cheat.
</P>
<P>
Aleksandr Bagach, who won the men's shotput world title at the
meet, was one of the five caught in Athens, and his gold medal
was stripped off.
</P>
<P>
Commending on the revised doping sanctions, Nebiolo said he
wanted to focus on what athletes did on the track or field,
rather than on what "turned up in their pee-pee."
</P>
<P>
IAAF also introduced a new Golden League including six elite
meetings for next season. The League will have a jackpot of one
million dollars to be divided equally amongst all athletes
winning his or her Golden League events and the Grand Prix final.
</P>
<P>
With a low key season looming in the year to come, IAAF will
trim off the prize money to 50,000 dollars for each world record
breaker in the League events.
</P>
<P>
Money is an effective incentive indeed, but sometimes it also
creates unpleasant odds and ends.
</P>
<P>
Is it a lesson IAAF has learned from this season? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors of Organs Reach Record Amounts In Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 30,000 Buenos Aires
dwellers have expressed this year their willingness to bestow
their organs, the Buenos Aires Provincial Health Ministry`s Center
of Ablation and Implants (Cubaiba) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A Cubaiba`s report says that the will to donate organs and
the donation itself are increasing in this Argentine province.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1996, ablations rose by 21 times and operations
performed by the Cubaiba increased by 13 times.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 only nine ablations were done, 81 were done in 1993;
115 in 1994; 165 in 1995 and 188 last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It added that the increment in the donation of organs allowed
to hit the record amount of 14 donors per one million inhabitants
annually, which represents for the province the highest donation
rate in Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
