<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Money Creates Insane Results (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Money is not always a good
thing, at least this was somewhat true for world track and field,
in the year of 1997.
</P>
<P>
With prize money paved on the track of the Worlds for the
first time, Wilson Kipketer and a bunch of African gangling
runners plotted some cunning tricks to tarnish the world
championships, but salvaged an otherwise bleak season with a late
burst of record-cracking spree.
</P>
<P>
The year witnessed that the International Amateur Athletics
Association (IAAF) bent its obstinate head to the
boycott-threatening world elite by offering prize money to the
medal winners and world record setters at the Athens meet.
</P>
<P>
In order to make the championships a summit meeting of the
global best, a wild-card policy hastily set in motion by IAAF
president Prime Nebiolo to avoid the absences of American
superstars Michael Johnson, Gail Devers and other defending
champions.
</P>
<P>
IAAF even took a brave step to reduce the term of suspensions
for the use of steroids and other anabolics agents from four
years to two, and replaced the three-month punishment for less
serious drugs with a public warning.
</P>
<P>
After all these done, IAAF made the world believe that in the
birthplace of the modern Olympic movement, a new Athens' myth
would be created, and a number of world records would be
shattered.
</P>
<P>
But the whole thing ended like a hot joke.
</P>
<P>
No world records were set, an unprecedent shame in the meet
history, though an eye-popping cash of $100,000 offered right
there.
</P>
<P>
Only three world individual year best marks emerged during the
nine days, and only 10 of 44 Atlanta Olympic champions earned
gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Nebiolo, who masterminded the revolution of the track and
field, smelt a rat in the matter, but dared not to show his fury
at the end of his rope. If money is not the right thing to boost
athletes morale, what else?
</P>
<P>
Soon, crazy things exploded, in a blitz speed and a bizarre
manner. In a spell of two weeks after the championships, five
Africans blasted away world records seven times in four track
events. A phantasmagoria the sport had never experienced.
</P>
<P>
And moreover, the conspiracy got what they wanted -- 100,000
dollars for each record equally offered by IAAF at the less
prestigious Grand Prix meets.
</P>
<P>
At the Zurich Grand Prix meet on August 13, three days off the
Athens meet, three scintillating world records obliterated in an
electrifying 70-minute stretch.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan-turned-Dane Kipketer, who had lowered the world indoor
800 meters world record twice and tied the outdoor mark earlier,
shattered the 16-year-old record in one minute 41.24 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Then came the killing surge of Wilson Boit Kipketer in the
steeplechase. The Kenyan world champion, who is not related to
the famed 800m hero, flashed all the way to romp home in 7:59.08,
beating Moses Kiptanui's world record by 0.01 second.
</P>
<P>
"I hope my eight brothers and three sisters at home will
celebrate the record," beamed the 23-year-old.
</P>
<P>
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia, who set the 10,000m world
record in July, brought the packed crowd to their feet when the
tiny man with a huge heart crossed the line with another amazing
record in the 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed as a terrorist on the track, the smiling dwarf murdered
world champion Daniel Komen of Kenya in cold blood with a late
relentless explosion, clocking 12:41.86.
</P>
<P>
Gebrselassie's smile frozen on the face nine days later when
he heard two heart-broken news -- his miraculous double records
were swept into a rubbish can by a pair of Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
Having left Zurich somewhat miffed at losing his 5,000m world
record -- and especially at how it was lost -- Komen wanted to
land a punch on his rival's smiling face, and he finally made it
at Brussels Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Komen's race was quite the antithesis of a Gebrselassie run.
For the Kenyan, the pace was quick but quite metronomic
throughout. Yet the result was just fabulous -- 12:39.74, more
than two seconds faster than the short-lived record.
</P>
<P>
Poul Tergat's 26:27.85 performance in the 10,000m dropped a
handful salt in Gebrselassie's fresh wound. The Ethiopian had
made a vow in Athens: "If someone beats my world record, I will
train hard to take it back." But no words were heard from him
after that night.
</P>
<P>
The following day produced two more world records. The
record-guttler Kipketer went on to drop a bomb in the 800m with a
sensational time of 1:41.11, while Bernard Barmasai kicked Boit
Kipketer off the throne when he came from nowhere to gallop
7:55.72 in the 3,000-meter steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
With three records set in the 800m, an unprecedented feat in
history, and a magnificent win at the IAAF Grand Prix finals,
Wilson Kipketer capped the crown of the Male Athlete of the Year
with overwhelming votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
