<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq Acts Better than Words </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is quietly acceding to
the demands of the arms-monitoring teams despite Iraq's hard-nosed
rhetoric about limiting U.N. weapons inspections, a senior U.S.
official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government says publicly that it did not let UNSCOM
(U.N. Special Commission) go to certain places, but it has not
blocked the teams from doing their job, the official said on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
On the ground, the inspectors "have not been refused access to
any site," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the inspectors had sought access to any site that Iraq
has declared off-limits, the official said: "The Iraqis have not
provided a list of what is off-limits, so it's hard to know what
those places are."
</P>
<P>
But he said Iraq's public stance on arms inspections was
"unacceptable," and predicted that the U.N. Security Council would
pass a resolution condemning it sometime this week.
</P>
<P>
Iraq briefly expelled U.S. members of the U.N. arms teams in
November on grounds they were spying, sparking a tense standoff
with the United Nations and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration insisted that it has not ruled out any
option while increasing diplomacy in addressing the dispute with
Iraq in recent weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
