<HEADLINE> German Police Ends Greenpeace Blockade of Plutonium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- German police has put an end to a
14-hour dramatic blockade of a plutonium shipment launched by
Greenpeace protesters early today in the northern German port of
Bremerhaven, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Ten German maritime police officers had spend several hours to
release the seven Greenpeace protesters who chained themselves to
the entry ramp of a ferry early this morning in a move to prevent
the plutonium from being loaded. The police operation was taken
after several hours of fruitless negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports a police spokesman as saying that the ferry had
already left Bremerhaven this evening for Scotland where its
59-kilogram highly radioactive cargo will be reprocessed.
</P>
<P>
The plutonium stemming from a nuclear research center in
Karlsruhe had been transported to Bremerhaven from a storage depot
in Hanau. The Greenpeace had demanded the nuclear materials be
sent back to Hanau and called on the port authorities to declare a
future ban on similar shipments to abroad.
</P>
<P>
Before the police moved in to end the Greenpeace blockade, the
plutonium shipment had to be secured in a container storage area
in the Bremerhaven port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
