<HEADLINE> German Unemployment to Worsen as Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A leading German research
institute Monday said it expected Germany's unemployment to worsen
in the coming months in the wake of declining business confidence.
</P>
<P>
Ifo-Institute in Munich based the prediction on its November
survey results, which showed the business climate index in western
Germany slipped to 99.1 points from 99.7 points in October, while
that in the eastern Germany down to 102.9 points from 103.5
points.
</P>
<P>
Companies in the western part of the country are faced with
weaker foreign demand, and those in the eastern area see business
climate no longer as favorable as in past months.
</P>
<P>
The institute, one of Germany's six leading economic think
tanks, pointed out particularly dark prospects for Germany's
construction sector, expecting one third of building companies in
the west and 53 percent of those in the east to reduce jobs.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted job losses in the wholesale and retail
sector, saying that 12 percent of retailers in the west and 20
percent of those in the east were considering cutting payrolls due
to a drop in sales volume.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the institute revised its 1998 economic growth
projection down to 2.6 percent from 2.8 percent it previously
forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
