<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Higher on Tokyo Stock Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose against
other major currencies Monday after Japanese stocks plunged to a
more than 2 years low and a major U.S. rating firm downgraded the
credit ratings of four Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 130.13 yen,
up from 128.93 late Friday, in quiet trading ahead of the
Christmas holiday. The U.S. currency also was changing hands at
1.7810 marks, up from 1.7753.
</P>
<P>
The dollar strengthened early as Japanese stock prices
plummeted on fears that more ailing Japanese companies may fold
following Friday's collapse of food company Toshoku Ltd. -- the
ninth publicly traded concern to fail this year.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Exchange's major index sank 3.4 percent to its
lowest close since July 1995.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was buoyed by growing worries about Asia's
economic future after Moody's Investors Service lowered credit
ratings in Indonesia, Malaysia, South Korea and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4398 Swiss francs, up from 1.4253; 5.9570 French francs, up from
5.9400; 1,745.75 Italian lire, up from 1,741.25; and 1.4325
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4314.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6633 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6681 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
