<DOCNO> XIE19971223.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-End PCs Begin to Gain Bigger Retail Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Compaq continues to lead in
retail sales of personal computer in the U.S. market, according to
the PC Data November Retail Hardware Report released today.
</P>
<P>
During the month of November, Compaq captured 29.9 percent of
the unit sales of Intel-based PCs, registering a unit sales gain
of 35.6 percent over October and 60 percent over November 1996.
Compaq did however drop almost 1.5 percent in market share from
October, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Packard Bell-NEC was in second place with 23.6 percent of unit
sales, down more than 5 percent from October, on a unit sales
increase of 15.9 percent. Packard Bell-NEC's units were 60 percent
above last November. Hewlett-Packard was third, with 16.2 percent,
registering the same market share as in October.
</P>
<P>
IBM finished fourth at 7.6 percent with unit sales up more than
85 percent versus October and CTX International was fifth with 6.8
percent of the unit sales.
</P>
<P>
Overall, PC unit sales were up 41.6 percent above October's
figures, and 15.4 percent versus November 1996. However, this was
the fourth consecutive month showing declining unit sales growth
over the prior year.
</P>
<P>
Average selling prices were down to 1,333 U.S. dollars in
November, a 1.8 percent decline from October, and a 238 U.S.
dollar decline from last November.
</P>
<P>
Packard Bell-NEC was the leading manufacturer in the under
1,000 U.S. dollar market in November, with 28.1 percent, followed
by Compaq, CTX International and Hewlett-Packard. This was the
first month since June 1997, that Packard Bell-NEC was the king of
the low priced segment.
</P>
<P>
Packard Bell-NEC was also the leading manufacturer in the 1,000
U.S. dollar to 1,500 U.S. dollar price points, as it has been four
of the last five months. Hewlett-Packard was the number-one brand
between 1,500 U.S. dollars and 2,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
By price point, the largest unit increases were in the 2,000
U.S. dollar to 2,500 U.S. dollar price range, where unit volume
tripled over October, and market share doubled. Compaq dominated
these sales, accounting for over 50 percent of the volume within
these price ranges, the report said.
</P>
<P>
PC with Pentium II, the high-end central processing units
(CPU), continued to gain share in November. Pentiums with MMX
technology captured 60.7 percent of the market on unit growth of
just over 20 percent. Both Pentium II and AMD K6 processors
remain neck and neck in unit volume, and have both tripled volume
and doubled market share since October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
