<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Bosnian Leaders to Safeguard Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zagreb, December 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
told the leaders of Bosnia's three ethnic people Monday they must
safeguard peace and pledged to support those who were ready to
build a united Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On one-day visit to political leaders and U.S. forces serving
under the NATO-led peacekeeping force, Clinton made heartfelt
speech in the city's ornate national theater after walking through
the town.
</P>
<P>
"I come before you with a message for those in whose hands the
future of Bosnia lies-its leaders and its people. For in the end
future is up to you," he said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of Bosnia's three ethnic factions had made a
"fateful choice for peace when they signed the Dayton peace
accords in Ohio two year ago, ending the country's three and a
half year war, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But this responsibility and yours did not end there on that
day. In fact it only began. Your responsibility is to turn the
documents signed in Dayton into a living reality."
</P>
<P>
"To make good on the pledge to bring Bosnia together in one
county with two multi-ethnic parts sharing a common destiny."
</P>
<P>
In a clear warning to those who have obstructed the peace
process, Clinton said,"those who rise to that responsibility will
have the full support of the United States and the international
community. Those who shirk it will isolate themselves."
</P>
<P>
"The world which continues to invest in your peace rightfully
expects that you will do you part," Clinton told the leaders."More
importantly, the people of this country expect results and they
deserve them."
</P>
<P>
He said the people of Bosnia had to make their desire for peace
and a common future clear" to their leaders and support them in
the hand decision needed for a common future.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president and his entourage were flying this afternoon
to the northeastern town of Tuzla where he was meeting U.S.
troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
